{[%evp 0,9,34,28,74,66,74,74,75,57,77,32]} 1. e4 g6 {The Modern defence is a
go-to opening for many Black players when they need to play for a win,
particularly against lower-rated players. It keeps the pieces on the board and
the game gets complicated. As White, we should be very happy to face this as
we can gain a lot of space in the center and should be better objectively.
However, it is important to know our setups and the typical ideas as it is
very easy to overextend our centre.} (1... b6 {I don't have a great opinion
about 1...b6 and even 1.b3 :) Black allows us to grab full control over the
center and we should be able to get a sizeable edge.} 2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3 {
I like to keep the c3 square open for either the pawn or the knight. We check
this in the final chapter.}) (1... Nc6 {This is often used when Black needs to
play for a win at all costs.} 2. Nf3 {Objectively, this is not the most
critical move because Black has the option to go for 2. ..e5 and transpose.
However, it should not bother you unless you intend to go for something like
the King's gambit :) Most players who go 1.. .Nc6 are intending to get an
unbalanced game and we will not give them that so easily.} d6 {This is the
only way I see Black fighting for a win and I have faced this a few times
against good players even in classical chess. It leads to slightly unorthodox
positions where the theory has not been established clearly.} 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3
{Here there are a few options for us. I usually do not like going for the move
d5 early as it often leads to KID-like positions which is what Black is aiming
for. The move I always went for is 4.c3 which gives us a pleasant edge.
However, I feel we can play a bit more aggressively here and make use of
Black's risky play.}) (1... d5 {Another big favourite among club players- the
Scandinavian. People get very excited to bring the queen out too early but it
often backfires with the queen getting pushed around.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 (2... Nf6 {
This is a combination of the Alekhine and the Scandinavian. It is slightly
safer than the main lines but leads to more passive positions for Black.} 3. d4
Nxd5 4. Nf3 {We do not rush with the move c4. I have a general rule in
openings to play the most necessary move first to preserve flexibility. Here
the knight belongs on f3 while we can play without c4.}) 3. Nc3 Qa5 {The main
line in the Scandinavian and probably the most fighting line for Black. It is
not completely sound but the queen does have the potential to create some play
on the queenside.} (3... Qd8 {I always felt strongly that this just could not
be sound wasting two moves with the queen and I had zero preparation against
this opening until I became a GM. In recent times it has been played by a few
strong players, albeit in mostly blitz games. There are a few ways to get an
edge here and we will try to go for the most ambitious one.}) (3... Qd6 {
This has gotten popular over the last few years. The queen is safer here
compared to a5 but also less threatening. He stops us from getting the bishop
to the ideal h2-b8 diagonal.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. g3 {We want to fianchetto
the bishop and prepare the move Bf4. I like this move also because it is
consistent with our general plans.}) 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 {There are many
different plans here for Black. Modern theory has established that the best
lines for Black are those with the move Bf5- either directly or after c6. The
other lines are more or less refuted with correct play.}) (1... Nf6 {The
Alekhine- a favourite of club players. I feel people get some kind of pleasure
from provoking the opponent to advance his pawns forward :) We should be
careful not to underestimate these openings as there is a real danger of
overextending our center. I have seen this happen frequently in my Blitz games.
} 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 {We go for the most principled line- the four pawns attack.
The advantage of this line is that the lines are quite dynamic and concrete.
The other lines with d4 depend a lot on the understanding of the typical
middlegames. Here, the value of experience is much less than the value of
concrete knowledge.} Nb6 4. d4 d6 5. f4 {We have four pawns in the center of
the board. We will aim to keep control over these pawns and finish our
development. If we manage to achieve that we would usually be much better. the
most ambitious move gaining a lot of space in the center.} dxe5 6. fxe5 {
We open up the 'f' file and maintain our two pawns in the center.} Nc6 7. Be3
Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 {There are a few different plans for Black here. I
believe that the best plan is definitely to castle short and break with f6
which we will look at in the 7th chapter. We will look at sidelines in the 6th
chapter. Castling queenside is quite risky with our central pawns and a4-a5
comes very quickly.}) (1... d6 {The Pirc Defence is a slightly more solid
version of the Modern Defence in my opinion. However, as always less risk
means less reward and Black's play on the queenside is usually slower.} 2. d4
Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 {This is the main line of the Pirc defence. There are several
ways here to pose serious problems for Black as he is giving up control over
the center. I want to go for a system which is critical but also cuts down on
the amount of lines we have to remember. We will be looking at a few of these
sidelines in the 3rd chapter.} (3... c6 {The only real point of this move
order seems to be able to get the move Qa5 quickly. It allows us to expand in
the center freely.} 4. f4 {We punish Black for going for a non-developing pawn
move so early.}) (3... Nbd7 {Usually here we will transpose after the move Nf3
but since we play 4.Nge2 we should look for an alternative. It is not that
difficult though since we have a very principled option-} 4. f4 {We have seen
this move in the Pirc/Modern chapters. If Black plays slowly we can occupy the
entire center.}) (3... e5 4. Nge2 {This is a rare system against the Philidor
but I think it poses a lot of practical problems for Black. It takes him out
of his comfort zone in the positions after Nf3. There are two different plans
here- to go h3,g4 or get the knight to g3. We will decide based on Black's
development. We will look at this in the 4th and 5th chapters.} exd4 5. Nxd4
Be7 6. Bf4 {This is the best square for the bishop here keeping an eye on the
d6 pawn. We anticipate Black going for the move c5 in the future.}) 4. Bf4 {
This is the 10th (!!) most popular move in the position. This is slightly
misleading as it may well transpose to Be3/Bg5 lines after a future Qd2, Bh6.
It helps get control over the e5 square and delay Black from fighting back in
the center. This particular position is the subject of our 2nd chapter.}) 2. d4
Bg7 3. Nc3 {The knight usually belongs on c3 in these positions and I prefer
to have my pawn on c2. We mostly castle queenside and we do not want to commit
too many pawn moves there.} d6 (3... c6 {This is the 2nd most common move in
the position. Black prepares the move d5. Here we can just transpose to my
recommendation in the Caro-kann database after Nf3 and d5. But there are
better ways to get a big advantage,} 4. Be3 {This is the 3rd most popular move
in the position but makes the cut partly due to its consistency with the main
lines. There are many moves which lead to an edge for White but it is
important to be able to remember the details easily.} d5 5. e5 {The bishop on
g7 is not that well placed and is restricted by our pawn chain.}) 4. Be3 {
This is our usual developing style in these positions. We put this bishop on
e3/f4 and get our queen to d2. We will almost always castle queenside.} a6 {
This is the main line of the Modern variation. Black wants to go b5 next and
fight back against our center. He is breaking some general principles by not
developing his pieces quickly.} (4... c6 5. f4 $1 {If given the chance we will
take control of the center.}) 5. g4 $5 {This is the 7th most popular move in
the position! We are exploiting the knight on g8 and are planning to go h4-h5
next. Black has to try and create some counterplay quickly. We will examine
this deeply in the 1st chapter.} *

