{[%evp 0,33,34,20,74,66,74,75,75,55,77,33,55,93,54,46,67,14,25,41,43,44,67,53,
77,70,144,111,112,96,19,56,129,107,80,80]} 1. e4 g6 {The Modern defence is a
go-to opening for many Black players when they need to play for a win,
particularly against lower-rated players. It keeps the pieces on the board and
the game gets complicated. As White, we should be very happy to face this as
we can gain a lot of space in the center and should be better objectively.
However, it is important to know our setups and the typical ideas as it is
very easy to overextend our centre.} 2. d4 d6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Be3 {This is our
usual developing style in these positions. We put this bishop on e3/f4 and get
our queen to d2. We will almost always castle queenside.} a6 {This is the main
line of the Modern variation. Black wants to go b5 next and fight back against
our center. He is breaking some general principles by not developing his
pieces quickly.} 5. g4 $5 {This is the 7th most popular move in the position!
We are exploiting the knight on g8 and are planning to go h4-h5 next. Black
has to try and create some counterplay quickly.} b5 {This is by far the main
move in the position and the natural continuation to a6.} (5... Nc6 {Is a
weird move played by Grishuk once.} 6. d5 {We kick the knight back and gain
space in the center.} Na7 7. a4 {We stop the knight from ever coming back into
the game.} (7. Bd4 $5 Nf6 8. g5 Nh5 9. Be2 c5 10. Bxg7 Nxg7 11. a4 $14) 7... c5
8. h4 h6 9. f3 $14 {We can continue normally with Qd2, Ne2. Eventually, the h5
break will be very strong.}) (5... Nf6 {The knight is not so well placed in
these lines. A common idea is now to go Nge2-g3 followed by g5.} 6. h3 {
The simplest preparing to develop our kingside pieces next.} h5 {Black tries
to justify the knight on f6 but it is just going to be pushed back.} (6... O-O
7. Nge2 {Ng3 and g5 is a big threat. It is not easy for Black to deal with it.}
Nc6 (7... b5 8. e5 $16 {[%cal Gf1g2]}) 8. f4 $14 {We can go Bg2 and e5 next.})
(6... b5 7. e5 $16) 7. e5 $1 dxe5 8. dxe5 {We are happy to trade the queens
and in the resulting endgames, our space advantage will give us a nice edge.
Playing with space advantage we can exchange the major pieces- the key point
is to preserve minor pieces.} Qxd1+ 9. Rxd1 Nfd7 10. f4 {Our center is much
more important than the g4 pawn. Nd5 is always in the air.} hxg4 11. Bg2 $14 {
We finish our development and can take on g4 on the next move.} gxh3 $6 12. Nd5
Kd8 13. Nxh3 {[%cal Gh3g5] The other knight is heading to g5 and Black is in
big trouble.}) (5... Nd7 {A natural development preparing to go c5 next.} 6. h4
{We continue with our plan to push h5.} c5 {Black immediately breaks in the
center following the general rule- play on the flank should be countered in
the center.} (6... h6 {The general consensus is to not make pawn moves on the
side where you are defending and this will help certainly us create our play
faster on the kingside later. On the other hand, he does manage to prevent the
immediate h5.} 7. Qd2 {We will first get our king to the queenside before
deciding on either h5 or g5.} (7. g5 $2 hxg5 8. Bxg5 c5 $17) 7... b5 8. f3 Ngf6
(8... Bb7 9. O-O-O e6 10. Nh3 {We keep the e2 square open for the other knight.
} Ne7 11. Kb1 $16 {Our next plan will be to go h5 and g5 can be met with the
f4 break, opening up the position.}) 9. O-O-O Nb6 {Black gets his knight to b6
before going for b4. Now, we cannot retreat to e2 since it allows Nc4.} 10. Nh3
b4 11. Nb1 a5 (11... h5 12. g5 Nfd7 13. Qxb4 {We just take the pawn and it is
not clear how Black is going to attack on the queenside.} O-O 14. Qd2 $14) 12.
c4 $1 $16 {This is an unusual but strong idea pushing the 'c' pawn with the
king on c1. We can go for the move c5 next. Black is not quick enough to
create any play against our king.}) 7. g5 $5 $146 {[%cal Gh4h5] We prepare the
move h5 and stop Black from going himself.} (7. h5 {was my first intention but
Black has the amazing move-} g5 $1 (7... gxh5 8. Rxh5 $14) 8. dxc5 Nxc5 9. Bxg5
{Now the position gets complex and Black gets some counterplay.} Qb6 10. Nd5
Qxb2 11. Rb1 Qxa2 12. f3 h6 13. Be3 Qa5+ 14. Qd2 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 $44 {We have
decent compensation here for the two pawns with the knight heading to b6 next.}
) 7... h6 {The only way to counter our plan.} 8. dxc5 {We need to release the
tension in the center first before going for our play on the Kingside.} (8. Nf3
{is also possible} Qa5 9. a3 hxg5 10. Nxg5 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6]}) (8. gxh6 Nxh6 9.
h5 Ng4 $1 $11) 8... dxc5 (8... Nxc5 9. Bxc5 {We are very happy to trade the
queens as the knight is stuck on g8.} dxc5 (9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 dxc5 11. Qxd8+
Kxd8 {unfortunately fails to the amazing} 12. h5 $1 $16 {A very nice tactical
idea!} hxg5 13. hxg6 Rxh1 14. gxf7 $18) 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Rd1+ Kc7 12. Nd5+
Kc6 13. Bg2 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5] The knight is a monster on d5 especially if
Black goes for the move e5.}) (8... hxg5 9. cxd6 Rxh4 10. Rxh4 gxh4 11. Nf3 $14
) 9. gxh6 Bxc3+ $1 {Black gives up his dark-squared bishop to damage our
queenside pawn structure.} (9... Nxh6 10. h5 $14) 10. bxc3 Qa5 11. Qd2 {
This position looks great for us with the pawn on h6 but Black can get enough
counterplay after} Nxh6 $1 {This does not look too difficult to find but the
continuation is by no means easy.} 12. f3 Ne5 $1 (12... Ng8 13. c4 Qxd2+ 14.
Bxd2 $14 {The bishop will be very well placed on c3 and we have the bishop
pair.}) 13. Bxh6 $5 {Looks winning for White but the computer manages to hold
miraculously which is practically impossible. There is very little chance of
all this occurring in our games.} (13. Kf2 Ng8 14. Bf4 $14 {White has a slight
edge here but Black could equalise with precise play.}) 13... Rxh6 14. Qxh6
Qxc3+ 15. Ke2 Qxa1 16. Qh8+ Kd7 17. f4 f6 $1 {The only move keeping the queen
stuck on h8.} 18. fxe5 Kc7 19. Nf3 Bg4 $3 {This has to be calculated
accurately. Unfortunately for us, Black does have a perpetual check.} 20. Qxa8
Bxf3+ 21. Kxf3 Qd1+ $11) (5... e5 $146 {It is a bit surprising that this move
has never been played before.} 6. h3 {We will just continue with Nge2 or Nf3
and castle Queenside. The knight on g8 has a tough choice as we are always
ready to go g5 and it is not very active on e7.} Nc6 $5 {Here there are
several ways to play. It depends on your style of playing. As an e4 players I
am not comfortable with KID positions and I would be hesitant to go there if
there are other options available.} 7. Nge2 (7. d5 Nd4 8. Nf3 Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 $14
{We have a nice space advantage and can continue playing on the kingside.})
7... exd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. Be2 $14 {Black's knight is completely misplaced and
we have a more clear plan. We will go Qd2 and then maybe h4-h5. We can delay
castling until the position clarifies a bit more.}) 6. Bg2 {We are preparing
to go for the move e5 if given the chance.} Bb7 7. h4 {h5 is coming up next.
Black has an important decision to make regarding his development.} h6 (7...
Nf6 {just allows} 8. h5 b4 9. Nd5 Nxd5 10. exd5 $16) (7... h5 $2 {This is
played very often in online blitz games but it is a clear mistake.} 8. gxh5
Rxh5 9. Bf3 Rh8 10. h5 $18 {White gets a huge initiative with a big lead in
development. He is almost winning already.} e5 (10... gxh5 11. e5 $1 $18 {
We get rid of Black's only active piece.}) 11. dxe5 Bxe5 12. hxg6 fxg6 13. Rxh8
Bxh8 14. e5 $1 {Again we are very happy to trade the bishops and get our
pieces out with tempo.} Nc6 15. Be4 Nge7 16. Qg4 $18 {1-0 (27) Caruana,F (2835)
-Gumularz,S (2518) Karlsruhe 2020}) (7... b4 8. Nce2 {The knight is heading to
g3 where it is quite well placed.} Nf6 (8... h6 9. c3 $1 {This is the other
benefit of Black pushing the pawn to b4.} bxc3 10. bxc3 $16 {[%cal Ge2g3]}) 9.
g5 {The knight lacks a good square.} Nh5 {We attack the knight immediately with
} (9... Nxe4 $6 10. f3 $18) (9... Nfd7 {allows} 10. h5 Nb6 11. h6 Bf8 12. d5 e5
13. dxe6 fxe6 {1-0 (52) Durarbayli,V (2606) -Mamedov,N (2609) Nakhchivan 2021}
14. Nh3 $18 {White is already winning here.}) 10. Bf3 $1 c5 11. Bxh5 gxh5 12.
Ng3 $16 {Black's kingside is in ruins.}) (7... Nd7 {is slow and allows our
simple plan-} 8. h5 $1 gxh5 (8... c5 9. h6 {This used to be underestimated by
a lot of players but with the advent of computers it is very common to get the
pawn to h6.} Bxd4 10. Bxd4 cxd4 11. Qxd4 e5 12. Qxd6 {1-0 (32) Christiansen, J
(2617) -Lagarde, M (2657) chess24.com INT 2020}) 9. g5 $1 {This is the key
point-we do not allow the knight to develop easily.} c5 (9... h6 {does not
help much} 10. Rxh5 c5 11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. Bd4 $16) 10. Nge2 {The knight is
heading to h5 next!} h6 11. Ng3 hxg5 12. Nxh5 Rh7 13. Nxg7+ Rxg7 14. dxc5 Nxc5
15. Rh8 $14 {We will go Qd4 and castle next. Black will struggle to find a
good place for his king.}) 8. g5 $1 {We need to keep the knight on g8
restricted.} hxg5 (8... h5 9. Nge2 {[%cal Gd4d5]}) 9. h5 $1 {We want to break
open the kingside! We can always take back on g5 with the bishop.} b4 {Black
gives up the pawn on b4 to help gain a tempo. He has to develop his pieces
quickly.} (9... e5 {allows} 10. dxe5 Bxe5 11. hxg6 {breaking apart his pawn
structure.} fxg6 12. Rxh8 Bxh8 13. Nd5 $16) (9... gxh5 {helps us open up the
position and get control over the 'h' file.} 10. Rxh5 Rxh5 11. Qxh5 Nd7 12.
Qxg5 Kf8 {1-0 (57) Ivic, V (2581) -Dubov, D (2710) Lichess.org INT 2021} 13. e5
$18 {Black's king is coming to come under huge pressure on f8.}) 10. Nd5 e6 11.
Nxb4 gxh5 12. Rxh5 Nf6 $1 {He gives a pawn now but gets decent counterplay.
None of the other moves poses any issues for us.} 13. Rxh8+ (13. Rxg5 Bh6 $132)
13... Bxh8 14. Bxg5 {We have won a pawn and now will look to consolidate our
position.} c5 15. dxc5 Qa5 16. c3 Qxc5 17. Be3 $14 {Black has to prove his
compensation for the pawn. Our king is reasonably safe on the queenside while
the same cannot be said for Black.} *

