{[%evp 0,23,34,20,74,74,75,75,72,72,61,50,68,61,91,37,42,16,27,-23,-15,-15,41,
16,26,8]} 1. e4 d6 {The Pirc Defence is a slightly more solid version of the
Modern Defence in my opinion. However, as always less risk means less reward
and Black's play on the queenside is usually slower.} 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 {
This is the main line of the Pirc defence. There are several ways here to pose
serious problems for Black as he is giving up control over the center. I want
to go for a system which is critical but also cuts down on the amount of lines
we have to remember.} (3... c6 {The only real point of this move order seems
to be able to get the move Qa5 quickly. It allows us to expand in the center
freely.} 4. f4 $1 {We punish Black for going for a non-developing pawn move so
early.} (4. Nf3 $5 {Might transpose back to the main lines.}) 4... Qa5 5. Bd3 {
We defend the pawn on e5. If we manage to get Nf3 and 0-0 easily, the game is
practically over.} e5 6. Nf3 Bg4 {This is the main move in the position.} (6...
Nbd7 7. O-O Be7 8. Be3 O-O 9. h3 Re8 10. Qd2 $16 {Black lacks counterplay.}) (
6... exd4 7. Nxd4 g6 {Black wastes even more time to fianchetto the bishop.
There are many ways here to get a big edge.} 8. O-O Bg7 9. Kh1 O-O 10. f5 $5 {
We want to go Qe1-h4 and attack the dark squares in the kingside.} Nbd7 11. Qe1
Re8 12. Qh4 Ne5 13. Nf3 $16) 7. Be3 Nbd7 {Black has gotten his bishop out
before going Nd7 but he will have to give up the bishop very soon.} (7... exf4
8. Bxf4 Qb6 9. Be3 Qxb2 10. Ne2 $16 {We will get more tempi playing against
the Black queen.}) 8. h3 {This has been played very few times but it makes a
lot of sense forcing Black to trade on f3.} exf4 (8... Bh5 9. g4 exf4 10. Bxf4
$16 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge1c1]}) (8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 exf4 (9... Be7 10. O-O-O $18) 10.
Qxf4 $1 $18 {This is the drawback of directly taking on f3. The queen is
perfect here.}) 9. Bxf4 (9. Bd2 $5 $16) 9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Qb4 {Black goes
after our pawns but there is a huge difference in development.} 11. Be3 $1 {
The d4 pawn is more important.} Qxb2 12. Kd2 Qa3 13. Rab1 $16 {White is close
to winning here with such active pieces.}) 4. Bf4 $1 {This is the 10th (!!)
most popular move in the position. This is slightly misleading as it may well
transpose to Be3/Bg5 lines after a future Qd2, Bh6. It helps get control over
the e5 square and delay Black from fighting back in the center.} (4. Be3 c6 (
4... a6 5. f4 Bg7 6. Nf3 $16) 5. Qd2 b5 {and white is not able to play e5
easily} 6. e5 Ng4 $11) 4... Bg7 {The main move. Black does not necessarily
have to castle immediately but the bishop belongs on g7. The one drawback is
that Bh6 comes with a tempo.} (4... Nbd7 5. Nf3 $1 {The usual response to Nbd7,
stopping the move e5.} (5. Qd2 e5 $132) 5... Bg7 {This will almost always be
met with Qd2 and Bh6.} 6. Qd2 c5 (6... O-O 7. O-O-O c5 8. Bh6 cxd4 9. Nxd4 $16)
7. Bh6 Bxh6 8. Qxh6 cxd4 9. Nxd4 $16 {The queen on h6 is quite annoying for
Black as his king remains stuck in the centre.}) (4... Nc6 {does not fit in
with Black's setup.} 5. Qd2 e5 (5... Bg7 6. O-O-O $16) 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+
Kxd8 8. Bg5 $16) (4... a6 {Is not that effective in combination with the move
Nf6.} 5. Qe2 $1 $146 {[%cal Ge4e5] With the knight on f6, e5 is a big threat
now.} Bg7 (5... b5 6. e5 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nd5 8. O-O-O $16) 6. O-O-O c6 (6... O-O
7. e5 $16) 7. h4 Qa5 8. Kb1 b5 9. e5 $16) (4... c6 {Black keeps his bishop on
f8 for the time being and prepares the move b5/ Qa5.} 5. Qd2 (5. Nf3 {This
will most likely transpose back to our main lines but there is one independent
option.} Qa5 $5 6. Bd2 {This is very rare but we want to force the queen back
to d8.} Bg7 7. Bc4 O-O 8. h3 Qd8 9. e5 Nd5 10. O-O $14 {Here the play is more
positional.}) 5... b5 {Black immediately starts play on the queenside.} (5...
Bg7 {transposes to the main line.}) (5... Nbd7 {Black prepares to go for the
move e5 and we react similarly to our main lines-} 6. Nf3 $1 Qa5 {Black again
prepares e5.} 7. Be2 e5 8. Bh6 $14 {We will castle on the kingside here.
Blacks play on the queenside does not make that much sense then.}) (5... Qa5 6.
O-O-O b5 7. e5 b4 8. exf6 bxc3 9. Qxc3 Qxc3 10. bxc3 $14) 6. Bd3 {We are
consistent with our usual plan.} (6. e5 $5 {this can be checked. It leads to a
better endgame.}) 6... Nbd7 (6... Bg7 {is just an indication for us to go} 7.
Bh6 $1 Bxh6 8. Qxh6 $16) 7. Nf3 {Again we stop the move e5 immediately.} Bg7 8.
Bh6 Bxh6 (8... O-O) 9. Qxh6 {The major problem for Black is that we have not
yet castled on any side. So he cannot go all out on the queenside. We can even
start playing positionally on the queenside in the future.} e5 (9... b4 10. Ne2
$16) 10. a4 $1 {Case in point! We exploit the move b5 and will probably castle
kingside next.} b4 11. Nd1 Ng4 12. Qd2 a5 13. h3 Ngf6 14. Ne3 $1 $16 {We have
changed our plans! We can go 0-0-0 and Ng4 next.}) 5. Qd2 c6 $1 {Black keeps
the king in the center for now. I think objectively this is the best try for
Black.} (5... Nbd7 {Now this does not make sense as we are in time to go long
castle stopping e5 ideas.} 6. O-O-O O-O 7. e5 Nh5 8. Bh6 $16) (5... O-O {
Black is jumping from the frying pan to the fire himself but this is the most
played move in the position.} 6. O-O-O {Bh6 is coming up next. We have a clear
plan to attack the kingside.} c6 {Black has to try and push his pawns on the
queenside. But we have a nice hook on g6 to attack faster.} (6... Nc6 {Black
is preparing to go e5 next and we have to be a bit careful.} 7. f3 {We can
continue with g4 and h4 next. It's not clear how Black can create any play.} (
7. Bh6 e5 $1 8. d5 Nd4 9. h4 c5 $1 $132) 7... h5 (7... Re8 {Black is preparing
to go e5 but we stop it with} 8. Bb5 $1 $16 {We can take on c6 after a6
stopping all counterplay.}) 8. Qe3 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5] Now e5 is a big threat for
us and Black also lacks the h5 square for the knight.} Qe8 9. e5 Nd7 10. exd6
cxd6 11. d5 Nce5 12. Bh6 $16 {The kingside is going to open up very soon.}) (
6... Nbd7 {transposes.}) 7. Bh6 b5 8. f3 $1 {We keep control over the center
and it is not easy for Black to do anything on the queenside.} Qa5 {Black is
going after the a2 pawn.} (8... b4 9. Nce2 Qa5 10. Kb1 c5 (10... Be6 11. Nc1
Nbd7 12. h4 $18) 11. h4 Nc6 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. h5 $1 {The typical idea to open
the 'h' file.} cxd4 14. hxg6 fxg6 15. Qh6+ Kg8 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Rxd4 Be6 18.
b3 $16 {Our queenside is fully secure now and we have a big advantage.}) 9. h4
$1 {In opposite-side castling middlegames, time is of the essence. We do not
care about the pawn on a2.} b4 10. Nb1 {h5 is coming up next and there is
nothing much that Black can do.} Qxa2 (10... Be6 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. h5 $18) (
10... Nbd7 11. h5 $18) (10... Ba6 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. h5 Nc7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14.
Ne2 $16 {We want to take and go Qh6 next. e5 is always in the air.}) 11. h5
Nbd7 12. hxg6 fxg6 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qh6+ Kf7 15. e5 $1 {We want to open up
the center too now.} dxe5 16. Nh3 Ke8 17. Ng5 $18 {There are many ways to
continue for us. We can bring our rook to e1 and Black is in a lot of trouble
with the king on e8.}) 6. Nf3 $5 {The third most popular move in the position.
What is the point? White is preparing to go Bh6 next but stops the move e5
which was annoying.} (6. Bh6 Bxh6 7. Qxh6 e5 $1 {[%cal Gd8e7]}) 6... b5 {
Black keeps the king in the center and starts his play on the queenside.} (6...
O-O 7. Bh6 {We have managed to go Bh6 and stop the move e5. h4 will follow up
next.} Bg4 (7... Qa5 8. h4 $16) 8. h4 $1 {We want to open up the 'h' file next.
Black cannot do much against this plan.} Nbd7 9. h5 $1 {Of course, we do not
care about sacrificing a pawn.} Bxh5 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. e5 $16 {[%cal Gf3g5]}) (
6... Qa5 {Black temporarily stops the plan of Bh6 and hints at going e5 in the
future.} 7. Bc4 $5 {This has been played only once and it makes sense because
we are inviting the move b5. But the point is that we want Black to weaken his
queenside with b5 and we are going to strike in the center soon. The bishop is
perfectly placed here to prepare e5-e6.} (7. O-O-O Bg4 8. Kb1 $14) (7. Bh6 $2
Bxh6 8. Qxh6 Nxe4 $17) 7... b5 (7... O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e5 $16 {[%cal Ge5e6]})
8. Bd3 Bg4 9. e5 Nh5 10. exd6 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nxf4 12. Qxf4 {So far all the
moves were kind of forced but here Black has a few options.} Qb4 {Looks like
Black recovers the pawn with a great position. Do we have anything up our
sleeve?} (12... e5 13. dxe5 O-O 14. Qg3 $14) 13. O-O-O Qxd6 14. Qxd6 exd6 15.
Nxb5 $1 {Yes, one of the points behind provoking the move b5! We are a healthy
pawn up now.} Kd7 16. Nc3 $14 Bxd4 $2 17. Bf5+ $16) 7. Bh6 O-O {This position
has occurred quite a few times by transposition.} (7... Bxh6 8. Qxh6 b4 {
Black goes after our central pawn.} 9. Nd1 Nxe4 10. Bd3 Nf6 11. O-O {We have a
huge lead in development and Black's king is stuck in the center. We are going
to break with a3 soon.} Ba6 (11... e6 12. Ne3 $16 {[%cal Ga2a3]}) 12. Bxa6 Nxa6
13. a3 $16 {It's not clear when Black is going to castle and we have
tremendous compensation for the pawn.}) 8. Bd3 {We keep an eye on e4 and next
up is the move h4.} Bg4 (8... Nbd7 {This is a bit cunning. Black wants to meet
h4 by taking on h6 and jumping to g4 with his knight. transposes.} 9. a4 $1 {
This was a surprising idea for me here as we have usually been focussed on the
kingside. Black was ready to meet the move h4 but he has kept his bishop
passive on the queenside. We are very flexible with the king still in the
center.} (9. h4 $6 Bxh6 10. Qxh6 Ng4 $1 11. Qd2 Ndf6) 9... b4 10. Ne2 a5 11.
Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Ng3 {Now we want to go h4-h5.} e5 13. Qg5 $1 (13. h4 Ng4 $1)
13... exd4 14. Nf5+ Kg8 15. Nxd6 $16 {Our knight is well placed on d6 and we
can continue with h4 or Bc4. We have a nice edge here.}) 9. h4 $1 Bxf3 (9...
Nbd7 {This has been played twice by Mamedyarov but we get a huge edge after}
10. h5 $1 Nxh5 11. Nh2 $5 Be6 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Nf1 $16 {[%cal Gf1g3] The
kingside is falling apart.}) 10. gxf3 Nh5 {Black manages to stop the move h5
currently but he cannot hold it forever.} 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. f4 $1 $14 {We can
go Be2 in the future and kick the knight back.} *

