{[%evp 0,25,34,26,75,74,74,72,84,55,68,40,38,35,49,39,42,27,21,21,21,4,24,2,2,
2,27,-7]} 1. e4 g6 2. d4 {In this chapter we will look at a few sidelines.
Black has a ton of different move orders and I will try to be consistent with
our plans, sometimes even at the cost of playing a slightly inferior move. I
have realised over the years that understanding our plans and ideas clearly in
these positions is much more important compared to concrete lines.} d6 (2...
Bg7 3. Nc3 {The knight usually belongs on c3 in these positions and I prefer
to have my pawn on c2. We mostly castle queenside and we do not want to commit
too many pawn moves there.} c6 {This is the 2nd most common move in the
position. Black prepares the move d5. Here we can just transpose to my
recommendation in the Caro-kann database after Nf3 and d5. But there are
better ways to get a big advantage,} (3... c5 {This almost transposes to some
kind of a Sicilian but having the knight still on g1 is in our favour.} 4. dxc5
Qa5 (4... Bxc3+ {Is too committal giving up the important dark-squared bishop.}
5. bxc3 Qa5 (5... Nf6 {This has been played several times by Hakobyan but
always in online blitz.} 6. e5 Ne4 7. Bc4 $1 {We are looking to go after f7
ourselves.} Nxc5 8. Nf3 $16) 6. Qd4 {The queen is heading to b4 kicking back
the Black queen.} Nf6 7. Qb4 Qc7 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. Qa4 Ne5 10. Be3 $16 {We have
managed to maintain our extra pawn with a big edge.}) 5. Nge2 $1 {This is the
advantage of having the knight still on g1. Given the chance, we will defend
the pawn with Be3 and get a huge edge.} Nf6 (5... Qxc5 {Black is wasting too
much time with his queen breaking the general principle- do not bring your
queen out too early.} 6. Be3 Qa5 7. Qd5 Qd8 8. O-O-O $16 {We have a huge lead
in development.}) 6. e5 {We want to use our development advantage and play
very dynamically.} Ng4 7. f4 Qxc5 8. Ne4 Qb6 9. N2c3 $16 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gh2h3]
The knights are dominating in the center of the board with Nd5 to follow next.}
) (3... a6 {This is similar to the main line in the Modern variation but
without the inclusion of the move d6.} 4. Be3 {We remain consistent with our
plan in these positions. We hint at going Qd2 and 0-0-0 followed by h4-h5 in
the future. I think this is the first plan that most of us learnt while
growing up and it is effective.} b5 {This is a bit premature but d6 would have
transposed back into the main line which we will look at in the next chapter.}
5. h4 $1 {We are immediately asking Black to decide his kingside. The Qd2 plan
is most effective once Black has played Nf6.} h5 {The most obvious response
but it does create a big hole on g5.} (5... Bb7 {Black gives us the chance to
go} 6. h5 $1 b4 7. Nd5 e6 8. Nxb4 Bxe4 9. Ne2 $16 {We have a lead in
development and a big initiative developing on the kingside.}) 6. Nf3 {This is
pretty rare but here we want to make use of the g5 square quickly.} Bb7 7. Ng5
{The knight cannot be kicked back now.} d6 8. g4 $1 {Lets open up the kingside.
} hxg4 (8... Nf6 9. gxh5 $16 {[%cal Gd1f3]}) 9. Qxg4 Nf6 {This has happened in
a couple of games. Where should we retreat with the queen?} 10. Qg1 $1 {
Probably the least likely square at first sight. We want to keep an eye on g6
and also prepare the move e5 by defending the rook on h1.} b4 11. Ne2 Nxe4 {
Happened in the game 1/2-1/2 (42) Darini, P (2426) -Tahbaz, A (2421) Rasht
2022. We now have the crushing sequence-} 12. Bg2 d5 13. Ne6 $3 {Boom! Blacks
Kingside is in ruins now.} fxe6 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Qxg6+ Kf8 16. Rg1 $18 {
[%cal Ge2f4]}) 4. Be3 {This is the 3rd most popular move in the position but
makes the cut partly due to its consistency with the main lines. As I
mentioned earlier there are many moves which lead to an edge for White but it
is important to be able to remember the details easily.} (4. Nf3 d5 {is a
direct transposition to Caro-kann.}) 4... d5 {The justification for Black's
previous move.} (4... d6 {transposes.}) (4... Qb6 {This is asking for trouble
breaking the general principles.} 5. a3 $1 {A simple way to stop the move Qb2.}
Nf6 6. Be2 {RIght now Qd2 is not possible and we just develop our kingside.
The queen on b6 is misplaced and Black has to retreat at some point.} (6. Qd2
$2 Qxb2 $17) 6... d6 7. h3 O-O 8. Nf3 {We do not want to play 0-0. Next, we
can go for the move g4. We are waiting for the queen to go back to go Qd2 and
0-0-0.} Qc7 9. Qd2 e5 10. O-O-O $16) 5. e5 {The bishop on g7 is not that well
placed and is restricted by our pawn chain.} Nh6 (5... Qb6 {does not achieve
much here} 6. Na4 Qa5+ 7. c3 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) (5... f6 {Black immediately
fights back against our center.} 6. f4 {Our plan next is to go Qd2 and castle
queenside. We can then go h4-h5 and start an attack on the kingside.} Nh6 (6...
Qb6 {This does not achieve much on the queenside as we can just go} 7. Na4 Qa5+
8. c3 Nd7 9. b4 Qc7 10. Nf3 $16) 7. Qd2 Ng4 (7... O-O 8. O-O-O $16) 8. O-O-O
O-O (8... fxe5 9. fxe5 Nxe3 10. Qxe3 O-O 11. Kb1 $16 {Next we start our play
on the kingside and I do not see Black surviving this.}) 9. Kb1 {This is a
useful move securing the king on the queenside. Now we can focus on our play
on the other side of the board.} b5 (9... Bh6 10. g3 b5 11. Nf3 Nxe3 12. Qxe3
Bg4 13. Be2 $16) 10. Nf3 Nd7 11. Bg1 $1 {Black missed his chance and now we
want to kick the knight back soon.} Nb6 12. Re1 $16 {We create a square on d1
for the knight and Black will struggle to create anything meaningful on the
queenside.}) (5... h5 {Honestly I do not understand this move much as it
weakens Black's kingside and gives us the chance to go for a potential g4 and
open up the kingside. It does not achieve much.} 6. h3 {We cover g4 and also
prepare a future g4 break.} Nh6 7. Nf3 $1 {This is pretty rare but makes a lot
of sense as the move h5 weakened the g5 square,} Nf5 (7... Qb6 {is a waste of
time} 8. Qd2 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ge1c1]} Qxb2 {is the only justification but} (
8... Nf5 9. O-O-O $16) 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. Bd3 $16 {White has a huge lead in
development and initiative. We can castle short next.}) 8. Bf4 {The bishop is
well placed here keeping an eye on e5. We have multiple plans here- Bd3, Ne2
or Qd2, 0-0-0.} Nd7 9. Bd3 Nf8 $5 {The knight will be well placed on e6.} 10.
Ne2 Bh6 (10... Ne6 {Black should not allow us to take on f5.} 11. Bxf5 gxf5 12.
Bc1 $18 {[%csl Rf5]}) 11. O-O Bxf4 12. Nxf4 Ng7 13. c3 {We have a big edge
with a nice space advantage. After Ne6 we can just come back to e2,
maintaining minor pieces on the board.}) 6. Qd2 $5 {We do not need to go for
the move f4 now as the knight has already gone to h6. We can just take on f6.}
(6. f4 {Is possible but I do not want to fully close our bishop.} Qb6 $1 {
This is different here with the inclusion of Nh6 and f4. It is still better
for us but there is no need to allow it.} 7. Na4 Qa5+ 8. c3 Nd7 9. b4 Qc7 10.
Nf3 O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a5] Black wants to go b5 and a5 next.}) 6... Ng4 $1 {
Black has to prepare the move f6 and the knight is essential there.} (6... Nf5
{The knight is not that well placed here and restricts its own pieces.} 7. Bf4
{g4 is a big threat now.} h5 {This again weakens the g5 square badly.} (7... c5
8. dxc5 d4 9. Ne4 $16) 8. Nf3 $1 Nd7 (8... O-O 9. h3 $18 {[%cal Gg2g4]}) 9. Bd3
Nf8 10. Ne2 $16 {We can even castle kingside here. We have better-placed
pieces and a nice space advantage.}) 7. Bf4 {h3 is a killing threat and Black
is forced to go} f6 (7... h5 8. O-O-O $16 {h3 will come up next.}) 8. exf6 Nxf6
{Now there are a few options for us to continue our play.} 9. O-O-O {We will
first secure our king on the queenside before starting our play. The other
benefit is that Black has to make up his mind first regarding his king.} (9.
Bh6 {Is the most played move but Black does not need to castle on the kingside
here.} Bxh6 $1 (9... O-O 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. O-O-O b5 12. Re1 b4 13. Nd1 $16) 10.
Qxh6 Bf5 11. O-O-O Qd6 12. h3 Nbd7 13. g4 Be6 14. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3g6]} Rf8 15.
Qe3 a6 16. f4 $14) 9... O-O 10. f3 Nbd7 11. Kb1 {Next on the agenda is to go
g4,h4 and h5. Black does not have any hook to attack on the queenside while we
have a target on g6.} b5 12. g4 Nb6 13. h4 Nc4 14. Qc1 $16 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 3.
Nc3 {These first 3 moves are common across our Pirc/ Modern repertoire. We
will most likely develop our c1 bishop next and prepare 0-0-0.} Bg7 (3... a6 4.
Be3 b5 {This is very similar to a line which we looked at earlier and we do
the same.} 5. h4 $1 h5 6. Nf3 $16 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gf3g5] The knight is heading to
g5 next.}) (3... c6 {With the knight on f6 we go for the move Bf4 keeping an
eye on the e5 square. Now it is not as effective as Black can get the move e5
more easily.} 4. Be3 (4. Bf4 Bg7 {[%cal Ge7e5]}) 4... Nf6 {Black keeps the
bishop on f8 which eliminates the Bh6 idea.} (4... Bg7 {transposes.}) 5. h3 $5
{We first cover g4 and retain the option to go for f3 next.} (5. Qd2 b5 {
Black benefits not having played the move Nf6.}) 5... Nbd7 (5... Bg7 6. f4 {
will transpose back into the main line soon.}) 6. f4 b5 7. a3 Nb6 (7... a6 8.
e5 Nd5 9. Nxd5 cxd5 {This is a great pawn structure for us.} 10. Nf3 $16) 8.
Bd3 Bg7 9. Nf3 $16 {We will just castle next with a big edge.}) 4. Be3 {
We played Bf4 in the previous chapter but the idea remains similar. We want to
go Qd2 and get our bishop to h6. On f4, we were able to control the e5 square
with Nf3 in many lines. Here, Black playing e5 is not such an issue and we
might go for f4 in some lines.} (4. Bf4 {is not that effective with the knight
still on g8.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7d4,Gc6d4]}) 4... c6 {Black delays the
development of the knight.} (4... Nf6 {This is similar to the previous chapter.
} 5. Qd2 {Allowing Bh6 would likely transpose back to the main line. We will
look at a few sidelines.} O-O {It is really risky as we are already hoping to
play on the Kingside.} (5... Ng4 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 $16) (5... c6 6. Bh6 {
another file}) 6. O-O-O c6 7. Bh6 b5 8. f3 Qa5 9. h4 {another file}) (4... Nc6
{Black is trying to provoke us into playing the move d5. That is not a bad
idea but we can just continue with our usual plan.} 5. Qd2 e5 6. Nge2 {We do
not want to close the center. We will maintain the tension for as long as
necessary.} Nf6 7. f3 O-O 8. O-O-O exd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be6 11. g4 $1 {
Opposite side castling on the board and it is time to start our play on the
kingside.} c5 12. Be3 Qa5 13. Bh6 Rfd8 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. h4 Bxa2 {Happened in
the game 1-0 (28) Najer,E (2633) -Mamedyarov,S (2753) Khanty-Mansiysk 2013 and
White could have won after} 16. h5 $1 $18) (4... Nd7 {This is a pretty unusual
move order. We have a few ways to deal with it but I like to try and exploit
his play by gaining space in the center.} 5. f4 a6 6. a4 b6 (6... e6 7. Nf3 Ne7
8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O $14 {We get a pleasant edge with a great center.}) 7. Nf3 Bb7
8. Bd3 e6 {Black has played a hippopotamus kind of system while we develop all
our pieces naturally on active squares.} (8... Ngf6 9. e5 $16) 9. O-O Ne7 (9...
c5 10. f5 $1 exf5 11. exf5 Ngf6 12. Qd2 O-O 13. Bh6 $14) 10. f5 $1 exf5 11.
exf5 O-O (11... Nf6 12. Qe1 $14 {[%cal Ge3g5,Ge1h4] The queen is perfect on h4
in these positions.}) 12. fxg6 hxg6 13. Ng5 $16 {Qe1-h4 is coming up next.}) 5.
f4 $1 {If given the chance we will take control of the center.} Nf6 (5... Qb6
6. a3 {A clever way to defend the pawn on b2. The pawn on a3 is usually quite
useful in these positions.} Nf6 7. Nf3 O-O (7... Bg4 8. Rb1 {Now this makes
sense since we need to take on f3 with our queen.}) 8. h3 $16 {We stop Bg4 and
are preparing to just go Bd3 next. There is no hint of any counterplay for
Black.}) 6. Nf3 {Now we do not need to go all out on an attack on the kingside.
We can focus on finishing our development and keeping control over the center.}
O-O (6... b5 7. a3 $16) (6... Qa5 7. Bd3 $16) 7. h3 {We cover the g4 square
and prepare to go e5 next.} Nbd7 (7... b5 {falls right into our plans} 8. e5
Nd5 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10. Qd2 a6 11. Bd3 Nc6 12. O-O $16) 8. e5 {These resulting
structures are quite good for us with the pawn on e5 and a big space advantage.
} Nd5 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10. Bd3 Qb6 11. Qc1 dxe5 12. dxe5 Qc7 13. Qd2 {We will
