{[%evp 0,29,20,31,75,74,72,68,71,32,29,5,13,-5,19,8,25,9,12,13,30,46,44,11,44,
8,8,6,6,-41,20,-8]} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {This is the Philidor
variation and it can arise via two different move orders- the one which we are
seeing and 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 d6. I never considered this variation seriously until
a couple of years ago when I faced this in 2 games against a Serbian GM. There
are multiple ways to play for us but Black usually goes for the same system
and can play pretty quickly. We need to know some ideas in the middle game to
maintain our advantage.} (3... Nbd7 {Usually here we will transpose after the
move Nf3 but since we play 4.Nge2 we should look for an alternative. It is not
that difficult though since we have a very principled option-} 4. f4 $1 {
We have seen this move in the Pirc/Modern chapters. If Black plays slowly we
can occupy the entire center.} e5 5. Nf3 exd4 (5... c6 $6 {This is just really
bad.} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. fxe5 Ng4 8. e6 $1 {We weaken Black's king by going after
the important 'f' pawn.} fxe6 9. Ng5 Nde5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. h3 Nh6 12. Bf4 $16
{We have a huge edge in the position with 0-0-0 to follow.}) 6. Qxd4 {With the
knight on d7 the queen on d4 is well placed. Black has to do something quickly
or risk getting crushed by our center.} c6 7. Be3 d5 $1 {This is the only
chance for Black. It happened in one of my games and I did not react correctly.
} (7... Be7 8. O-O-O $16 {White again has a huge edge here.}) 8. e5 $1 {
We do not get tempted by material and instead maintain control over the center.
} (8. exd5 Bc5 9. Qd3 Qe7 10. Kd2 cxd5 11. Re1 O-O $13) 8... Ng4 9. Bg1 {
This is necessary but the bishop is not doing that bad here.} Bc5 10. Qd2 Bxg1
11. Rxg1 Qb6 12. Na4 $1 {We force Black to trade queens and get into a bad
endgame.} Qe3+ 13. Qxe3 Nxe3 14. Bd3 b5 15. Nc3 $16 {We can go Nd4 next. White
is much better here.}) 4. Nge2 $5 {This is a rare system against the Philidor
but I think it poses a lot of practical problems for Black. It takes him out
of his comfort zone in the positions after Nf3. There are two different plans
here- to go h3,g4 or get the knight to g3. We will decide based on Black's
development.} Be7 {The natural move getting the king to safety quickly.} (4...
Nc6 {Was played by Jobova a few times. It is a good version of KID-like
positions for us.} 5. d5 Ne7 6. Bg5 Ng6 7. Ng3 {The knight can head to h5 or
f5 and we are also threatening Bb5+.} Be7 (7... h6 8. Bb5+ $16) 8. Nf5 Nxe4 (
8... Bxf5 9. exf5 Nf8 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Bb5+ $16 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gg2g4,Gg4g5] The
king is stuck on e7 now.}) 9. Nxg7+ Kf8 10. Bh6 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Kg8 12. Nh5 Bf8
13. Be3 $16 {The black rook is stuck on h8 and we have very good chances to
create an initiative on the kingside.}) (4... Nbd7 {This was the main line
after Nf3 and I expect it to be played often here too. However, compared to
those lines the knight does not have to defend the pawn on e5.} 5. a4 $5 {
This has been played only once out of 700+ games. We want to gain further
space with a5 in the future. We are also waiting for Black to commit to a plan
to develop his kingside.} c6 (5... Be7 {This is usually an indication to go
Ng3-f5.} 6. Ng3 O-O 7. Be2 c6 8. O-O $14 {Nf5 is coming up next.}) 6. a5 {
This pawn will be a thorn in Black's position for a long time. We always have
the idea of going a6.} Be7 7. Ng3 O-O 8. Be2 g6 9. O-O h5 (9... Re8 10. Be3 $14
{We can go for f4 next or prepare it slowly.}) 10. Bg5 Nh7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12.
Qd2 $14 {f4 is next on the agenda. Black is yet to finish development.}) (4...
c6 {This is an indication to go for the g4 plan since Black is delaying Be7 to
play on the queenside. It is slightly confusing but there is no established
theory here and I feel it is much harder to understand as Black.} 5. h3 b5 {
This is double-edged as it also creates some weakness for Black on the
queenside. d5 is often an idea now.} (5... Be7 6. g4 b5 7. Ng3 O-O 8. g5 Nfd7
9. h4 $14) (5... h5 {directly is not as effective as we can go} 6. a4 $1 {
We stop his play on the queenside and we can exploit his kingside.} h4 7. Be3
Be7 8. a5 $14) 6. a3 Be7 {is natural but we are just better after} (6... h5 $5
{This is an interesting plan to stop g4 but it does create some weaknesses
which we can exploit after} 7. Ng1 $1 {The knight will head to g5 soon.} (7. f4
{is also interesting.}) 7... Nbd7 8. Nf3 Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O $14) 7. g4 O-O
8. Ng3 Nbd7 9. g5 Ne8 10. h4 $14 {An attack is brewing on the kingside.}) 5. h3
O-O 6. g4 $1 {This is the point of our setup. A part of the plan is to play on
the kingside but at the same time, we can also castle kingside and go for the
move f4. The pawn on g4 actually helps fight for the center too as g5 is
always a threat.} c6 {The pawn belongs on c6 in these positions preparing an
eventual d5 or b5.} (6... exd4 {This has been played often- Black follows the
general principle to counter a flank attack in the center.} 7. Qxd4 $1 {
We need to keep an eye on d5 and not allow him to fight back in the center.}
Nc6 8. Qd1 {Black has not managed to get anything in the center.} Rb8 9. Bg2 b5
10. g5 $1 (10. a3 {1/2-1/2 (76) Nakamura,H (2568) -Campora,D (2510) Buenos
Aires 2003}) 10... Nd7 11. Qd2 $16 {We can even go for b3, Bb2 in the future.
0-0 and Ng3 will follow up next.}) 7. Bg2 {We are quick to stop d5 ideas. Now
there are a couple of ways to play for Black.} Nbd7 (7... Re8 {can be met with}
8. g5 Nfd7 9. h4 $14 {all of Black's pieces are cramped and undeveloped.}) (
7... b5 {Black immediately goes for his plan not giving us a chance to go a4.}
8. a3 (8. Ng3 $5 {is also possible but Black can close down the position after}
b4 9. Nce2 c5 10. d5 a5 {This depends on your taste- if you like this position
you can go for it.}) 8... h6 $146 {This is probably the best to stop g5.} (8...
a5 9. Ng3 $1 {The knight is heading to f5 and this makes a lot of sense now as
Black intends to go Bb7/a6 and prepare b4.} Ba6 10. Nf5 b4 11. Ne2 g6 12. Nxe7+
Qxe7 13. O-O $14 {The dark squares are now terribly weak on the kingside.}) 9.
O-O {Now we can go for the f4 plan. Ng3 is also possible anytime. Our king is
very safe.} Nbd7 10. Be3 Re8 (10... a5 11. Ng3 $14) 11. f4 exf4 (11... Nf8 12.
Qe1 $14 {The queen is perfect on f2 and we can bring our other rook to d1.})
12. Bxf4 {The bishop is well placed along this diagonal keeping an eye on d6.}
Nf8 13. Bg3 $14 {e5 is currently a threat. We can also consider going Qe1-f2.})
8. a4 {We take the chance to stop Black's activity on the queenside. Now g5
can be an idea next, especially if he goes for Re8.} a5 (8... Re8 {runs into}
9. g5 $16 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gg2f3]}) (8... h6 9. Be3 {We want to castle on the
queenside and open up the kingside. The pawn on h6 increases the strength of
the move g5.} Re8 10. Qd2 Nf8 (10... Rb8 11. d5 $5 $14 {another typical idea
to stop Black's play on the queenside before it can begin.}) 11. f4 {We open
up the 'f' file too.} Ng6 (11... exf4 12. Nxf4 $14) 12. O-O-O exf4 13. Nxf4
Nxf4 14. Bxf4 $14) 9. Be3 {It's hard to come up with a good plan for Black.} h6
10. Ng3 Re8 11. Qe2 $1 {We are playing against the d5 break and we want to get
our rook to the open file soon.} (11. Qd2 d5 $1 $132) 11... d5 {Black has to
look to fight back in the center.} 12. O-O-O Bb4 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Bd4 Nc4 15.
Qd3 $14 {f4-f5 is coming up next. We still maintain control over the central
squares.} *

