{[%evp 0,41,31,31,71,68,68,63,103,29,64,55,51,40,51,47,35,14,24,18,32,22,47,-5,
50,52,33,36,21,26,17,0,0,-37,-32,-32,32,32,46,-15,20,46,46,22]} 1. e4 d6 2. d4
Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nge2 exd4 {Black releases the tension in the center. This is
a concession from Black and helps us develop our pieces more easily.} 5. Nxd4
Be7 (5... g6 {Has been played occasionally by blitz players who want to get a
complex game but it has completely fallen out of fashion in classical chess.}
6. Be3 {We go with our plan from the previous chapters. These lines can even
transpose back into them.} Bg7 (6... Ng4 $5 {This has been played very few
times but it is the top choice of computers.} 7. Bf4 Bg7 8. Qd2 Nc6 {Black
wants to open up the 'b' file.} (8... O-O 9. f3 Ne5 10. O-O-O $16) 9. Nxc6 bxc6
10. h3 Ne5 11. Bh6 $1 {After the exchange of these bishops we can castle
safely on the queenside. The black king lacks a good square.} Bxh6 12. Qxh6 Qe7
13. O-O-O $14) 7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O {This is already clearly better for White.
I am not going to analyse this too deeply as our plan is simple- we want to go
f3, g4 and play on the kingside.} Nc6 9. f3 Re8 (9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be6 11. g4
c5 12. Be3 Qa5 13. Bh6 $1 {The typical idea getting these bishops off the
board.} Bxh6 14. Qxh6 $18) 10. g4 {We start our play on the kingside.} Nxd4 (
10... Ne5 11. g5 Nh5 12. f4 $18) 11. Bxd4 Be6 12. g5 $1 {This is actually
important getting the g7 bishop off the board. Otherwise it can become
dangerous along the long diagonal.} Nh5 13. Bxg7 Nxg7 14. h4 $16) 6. Bf4 $1 {
This is the best square for the bishop here keeping an eye on the d6 pawn. We
anticipate Black going for the move c5 in the future.} (6. g3 $5 {Is another
setup which I like with White but it is less aggressive.}) 6... O-O 7. Qd2 Nc6
(7... a6 {Is too slow.} 8. O-O-O b5 9. Be2 b4 (9... c5 10. Nf5 $16) 10. Nd5 $1
Nxd5 11. exd5 a5 12. g4 $16 {[%cal Gd4f5,Gh2h4]}) (7... d5 8. Ndb5 $1 {It is
important to remember this idea.} Bb4 {The line is quite forcing here.} 9.
O-O-O c6 10. Nc7 Nxe4 11. Qd4 $1 {A key move attacking b4.} (11. Qe3 Nxc3 12.
bxc3 Ba3+ 13. Kb1 Na6 14. Nxa8 Qa5 15. Bxa6 bxa6 $11) 11... Bxc3 (11... Nxc3
12. bxc3 Ba3+ 13. Kb1 $16 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gb6,Gd4] The queen on d4 controls all
the key squares on the queenside.}) 12. bxc3 Qe7 13. c4 $1 {The queen comes
back to defend.} Qa3+ 14. Qb2 Qa5 15. cxd5 Nxf2 16. Be2 Na6 17. Nxa8 Nxh1 18.
Rxh1 Nb4 19. Bc4 Qc5 20. Bd2 $1 Nxd5 21. Bxd5 Qxd5 22. Re1 $14 {It is not easy
for Black to win back the piece.}) (7... c6 {Black prepares both b5 and d5.} 8.
O-O-O b5 {The most popular move. It was also played by Magnus in a rapid game
but it is not that sound.} (8... d5 {Is the better move.} 9. f3 $1 {Has been
played only 2 times. We do not simplify the position.} dxe4 (9... c5 {does not
work} 10. Ndb5 d4 11. Nc7 $18) 10. Qe1 $1 {We do not allow him to trade queens
on the 'd' file. Where can the queen go now?} Nd5 11. Nxd5 cxd5 12. fxe4 $16)
9. f3 b4 10. Na4 $1 {This is the key move to remember and it gives us a big
edge.} (10. Nb1 $2 {0-1 (41) Dominguez Perez,L (2758) -Carlsen,M (2863)
Lichess. org INT 2020} Qb6 $132) 10... Bd7 {Black is going after our knight.} (
10... Qa5 11. b3 Rd8 12. g4 c5 13. Nf5 Bxf5 14. gxf5 $18 {[%cal Gh1g1,Gg1g8]
White was winning in the game 1/2-1/2 (31) Viani,A (2397) -Praggnanandhaa, R 
(2608) Chess.com INT 2020}) 11. g4 $1 c5 12. Nf5 {We give up the piece on a4
but win the rook on f8.} Bxa4 13. Nxe7+ Qxe7 14. Bxd6 $18) 8. O-O-O Nxd4 (8...
a6 {runs into} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. e5 $16) 9. Qxd4 Be6 {Now e5 is not as
effective with the bishop already on e6. Instead, we will look to start our
play on the kingside.} (9... a6 {allows us to go} 10. e5 $1 dxe5 11. Qxe5 Bd6
12. Qd4 Bxf4+ 13. Qxf4 Qe7 14. Bc4 $14 {[%cal Gh1e1] Black is forced to weaken
his pawn structure with Be6 and fe6. We will follow up with Rhe1 next.}) 10.
Be2 {This is the third most popular move here. It connects the rooks and also
prepares to go g4 next.} a6 (10... Nd7 11. h4 {We are preparing a pawn storm
on the kingside and also stopping Bg5.} a6 (11... Bf6 12. Qe3 Re8 13. g4 $16)
12. g4 Bf6 (12... b5 13. Qe3 $16 {We will follow up with g5 and h5 next.}) 13.
Qe3 Be5 14. Bxe5 dxe5 15. g5 $16 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 11. Qe3 {We are preparing to
go e5 in the future. The queen is heading to g3.} Qc8 $1 (11... Nd7 {is too
slow} 12. g4 b5 13. h4 Nc5 14. g5 $16) (11... b5 12. e5 $16) (11... Re8 {
Black anticipates the move e5 and creates some pressure along the 'e' file.}
12. Qg3 {Now again e5 is a big threat. This is similar to the main line.} (12.
e5 Nd7 13. exd6 cxd6 {[%cal Ge6a2,Ge8e3,Gf4d6]}) (12. h4 b5 (12... Qc8 $1 13.
h5 b5 $132) 13. e5 Ng4 14. Qg3 $16 {1/2-1/2 (27) Giri,A (2768) -Rapport,R 
(2745) Warsaw 2023}) 12... b5 (12... Qc8 {will transpose.}) 13. e5 Nd7 14. h4
$1 {[%cal Gh4h5] We stop the move Bh4 and will look to play h5-h6 next.} b4 15.
Ne4 Bf5 16. Bf3 $14) 12. Qg3 $146 (12. h4 $5 {is another option.}) 12... Re8 (
12... Nd7 13. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 13. e5 $5 {We want to open up the position
and gain control over the center as we have the more active pieces. I like
this as it forces Black to find precise moves.} (13. Kb1 {is also possible
with h4 to follow next.}) 13... dxe5 14. Bxe5 Bf5 $1 {Very important to stop
the move Ne4. It does expose the a2-g8 diagonal for our bishop.} 15. Nd5 Qe6
16. Bc4 {The bishop will pose a lot of problems for Black along this diagonal.}
Nh5 $1 {Black has to react concretely here.} (16... Qc6 17. Bb3 $14) 17. Qc3
Qxe5 $1 18. Qxe5 Bg5+ 19. f4 Rxe5 20. fxg5 Kf8 21. Bb3 $14 {Finally we get a a
slightly better endgame where we can play on with no risk. Of course, there
may be some objectively better lines but I think this poses good practical
problems for Black.} *

