{[%evp 0,47,31,31,61,59,53,56,56,38,31,3,25,7,36,36,36,40,43,43,48,47,47,59,53,
72,71,71,67,56,54,26,75,75,72,-56,0,0,0,0,25,34,32,76,75,75,58,-20,-21,42]} 1.
e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine- a favourite of club players. I feel people get some kind
of pleasure from provoking the opponent to advance his pawns forward :) We
should be careful not to underestimate these openings as there is a real
danger of overextending our center. I have seen this happen frequently in my
Blitz games.} 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 {We go for the most principled line- the four
pawns attack. The advantage of this line is that the lines are quite dynamic
and concrete. The other lines with d4 depend a lot on the understanding of the
typical middlegames. Here, the value of experience is much less than the value
of concrete knowledge.} Nb6 4. d4 d6 5. f4 {We have four pawns in the center
of the board. We will aim to keep control over these pawns and finish our
development. If we manage to achieve that we would usually be much better. the
most ambitious move gaining a lot of space in the center} dxe5 (5... g5 {
A desperate move but we do not need to respond to it.} 6. Nc3 dxe5 7. fxe5 Nc6
8. Be3 $16) (5... Bf5 6. Nc3 {will likely transpose to the main line after}
dxe5 7. fxe5 e6 {tr}) (5... g6 6. Nc3 {We usually start with this move. Nf3
should not be played very early as it allows Black to go Bg4 directly.} Bg7 7.
Be3 Be6 8. b3 O-O 9. Be2 $1 {We will wait a bit more before getting the knight
to f3.} (9. Nf3 {runs into} c5 $1 10. dxc5 N6d7 $1 11. cxd6 exd6 12. Qxd6 Nxe5
$1 $11) 9... dxe5 (9... c5 {does not work now} 10. dxc5 dxc5 (10... N6d7 11.
cxd6 exd6 12. Qxd6 $18) 11. Nf3 $16) 10. fxe5 c5 {Black is trying to break
open the center and make use of his lead in development.} 11. d5 $1 {We are
ready to give up the e5 pawn in return for quick development and play in the
kingside. Moreover, we will likely win the pawn on c5.} Bxe5 (11... Bc8 12. Bf4
$16) (11... Bf5 12. Rc1 $16) 12. Qd2 Bf5 13. Nf3 Bg7 14. Bxc5 $16) 6. fxe5 {
We open up the 'f' file and maintain our two pawns in the center.} Nc6 (6... c5
7. d5 e6 (7... g6 8. Nc3 {Our play is very simple here- Bf4 followed by Qd2
and long castle.} Bg7 9. Bf4 O-O 10. Qd2 e6 11. O-O-O exd5 12. cxd5 $16) 8. Nc3
exd5 9. cxd5 c4 10. d6 $1 {This is very rare to get in the opening but we can
completely restrict the bishop on f8.} Nc6 11. Nf3 Bg4 12. Bf4 Qd7 13. Be2 $18)
(6... Bf5 {Black has not committed his knight to c6 yet.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. Nf3 {
One the bishop is out to f5 we can go for Nf3.} Bb4 (8... Be7 9. Be3 O-O 10.
Bd3 $16) 9. Bd3 $1 {Getting the bishops off the board increases our control
over the center and also gets the queen to d3.} c5 10. Bg5 Qd7 11. Bxf5 exf5
12. d5 $16) 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 {There are a few different plans for
Black here. I believe that the best plan is definitely to castle short and
break with f6 which we will look at in the next chapter. Castling queenside is
quite risky with our central pawns and a4-a5 comes very quickly.} Bg4 {This is
the second most popular move but is a concession as he is moving the bishop
twice in the opening.} (9... Bb4 {is harmless} 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Na5 12. c5
Bxc3 13. bxc3 Nd5 14. Bd2 $16) (9... Nb4 {A desperate try to play against our
center but it does not achieve much.} 10. Rc1 c5 11. a3 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc6 13.
Nxf5 exf5 14. Be2 $16) (9... Qd7 {We should be very happy to see this plan as
we are going to castle on opposite flanks and this usually favours the side
with better control over the center.} 10. Be2 O-O-O 11. O-O Kb8 (11... f6 {
runs into the powerful} 12. d5 $1 Nxe5 (12... exd5 13. Bxb6 axb6 14. cxd5 $18)
13. Nxe5 fxe5 14. a4 $1 {Black is toast on the queenside.} a5 15. Nb5 $18) 12.
Rc1 $1 $146 {The rook is quite useful along the 'c' file and helps prepare Bc4
in some situations.} f6 13. c5 Nd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Qa4 fxe5 16. Bc4 Qe4 17.
Rfe1 $16 {We are close to winning here. Black has a lot of problems on the
queenside.}) 10. Be2 Bxf3 (10... Qd7 11. O-O O-O-O {I recently faced this in a
blitz game. Black players tend to play all these moves quickly and confidently
but are often almost losing with correct play.} 12. c5 $1 {The weakness on d5
is very well compensated by our play on the queenside and the space advantage.}
Nd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. b4 $1 Qe4 {All of this happened in one of my blitz games
(I was actually playing this blindfolded- I do it occasionally on a separate
account to improve my calculating skills) but I ended up blundering here.} 15.
Qd2 $1 (15. Qb3 $4 Nxd4 $1 16. Nxd4 Bxe2 17. Nxe2 $6 Rd3 $1 $17) 15... f6 16.
Rae1 $18) (10... Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. b3 {The Black knights are currently
useless on the queenside.} a5 13. h3 Bh5 14. Bd3 a4 15. g4 Bg6 16. Bxg6 hxg6
17. Qe2 $16) 11. gxf3 {Black has forced us to weaken our pawn structure
slightly but it does not matter that much as long as we retain good control
over the center.} Qh4+ 12. Bf2 Qf4 (12... Qh6 13. c5 Nd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Qb3
O-O-O 16. Qe3 $1 $16 {We are much better in the endgame after the exchange of
queens.}) 13. c5 $1 {I have realised that many players do not go for this move
because they do not want to give up control over d5. However, in reality, we
are often much better in these positions, especially with the pawn on d5. The
f8 bishop is completely out of the game and our light-squared bishop will be a
monster.} Nd7 (13... Nd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. O-O {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5,Gd1b3] We
will push the 'b' pawn up the board very soon.}) 14. O-O $1 (14. Qc1 {is the
main move and gives a big edge but it is not the best we can do.}) 14... O-O-O
15. Qa4 $1 {Why trade queens when we can attack the queenside much quicker
than Black?} f6 16. Bb5 Ndb8 17. Bc4 $1 {After forcing the knight to b8 we go
after the e6 pawn.} Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 19. Kh1 Bxc5 20. Bxe6+ Nd7 21. Rad1
Qxa4 22. Nxa4 Be7 23. exf6 gxf6 24. Rg1 $18 {[%cal Gg1g7] Black is in a bind
and we will soon end up winning material.} *

