{[%evp 0,47,31,31,56,62,62,64,49,26,26,25,36,43,47,47,51,51,49,48,49,49,26,34,
44,44,44,33,14,20,26,5,19,24,35,19,52,53,53,58,58,37,59,57,55,61,67,46,60,37]} 
1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. d4 d6 5. f4 dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3
e6 9. Nf3 Be7 {This is the best way to play for Black- he prepares to go f6
next and castle short. He gets a weak pawn on e6 but he manages to get some
control on the center. Our central pawn will come under fire.} 10. Be2 O-O (
10... Qd7 {This is weird combining different plans.} 11. O-O O-O-O 12. d5 $1 {
If you get the chance you should go for this break in the center.} exd5 13.
Bxb6 axb6 14. cxd5 Bc5+ 15. Kh1 Nb4 16. Nd4 $18 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5]}) 11. O-O f6 {
It is best to immediately break in the center. This is the most flexible
giving the queen a square on e7 next.} (11... Qd7 {Black delays the move f6
but the queen is shaky here. The white rook is coming to d1 very soon.} 12. Qd2
Rad8 (12... f6 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. Rad1 $16) 13. Rad1 {Now the threat is to go
for the move d5 and Black has to do something quickly.} f6 {The typical break
but a worse version of the main line.} 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Bf2 $1 $146 {This has
never been played before but it is a very strong regrouping of pieces that I
discovered when I was analysing these files recently. The queen is perfect on
the e3 square.} h6 (15... Bg4 {Black goes after our d4 pawn.} 16. Ne4 $1 Bxf3
17. Nxf6+ {We eliminate the dangerous dark-squared bishop and we enjoy the
pair of bishops.} Rxf6 18. Bxf3 $16 {Bh4 is a big threat now and Black is not
in time to win the pawn on c4.}) 16. Qe3 $1 Bh7 17. h3 $16 {We can continue
with improving moves such as b3, Kh1. Two ideas for us are to play Ne4 or Bd3
trading the bishops.}) 12. exf6 (12. d5 {is a forcing line but it only leads
to equality. I am just giving my analysis here without comments.} Nxe5 13. Nxe5
fxe5 14. g4 Bg6 15. dxe6 Rxf1+ 16. Qxf1 Bg5 $1 (16... c6 $5) 17. Bxg5 (17. Bf2
Qd2 18. c5 Qxb2 19. cxb6 Qxc3 20. bxa7 Be3 21. Rd1 Qc5 22. Rd7 Be8 23. Bxe3
Qxe3+ 24. Kh1 h6 25. Qf3 Qc1+ 26. Kg2 Qc2 27. Kf1 Qc1+ 28. Kg2 $11) 17... Qxg5
18. Qf2 (18. c5 Nc4 $1 19. h4 Qxh4 20. Bxc4 Qxg4+ 21. Kh1 Be4+ 22. Nxe4 Qxe4+
23. Kg1 Qg4+ 24. Kh2 Qh4+ $11) 18... Rf8 19. Qg3 Nc8 20. h4 Qf6 21. Rf1 Qxe6
22. Rxf8+ Kxf8 23. Qf3+ Ke7 24. Qxb7 Qb6+ 25. Qxb6 cxb6 $11) 12... Bxf6 13. Qd2
{Now Black has a few options for the queen. We are going to go Rad1 next.} Qe7
{This is the best square for the queen keeping an eye on the g5 square.} (13...
Qd7 14. Rad1 $16 {transposes.}) (13... Bg4 {does not make much sense here.} 14.
Rad1 Bxf3 15. Rxf3 $18) (13... Qe8 {allows} 14. Bg5 $1 {We trade off Black's
active bishop and get better control over the center.} Rd8 15. Bxf6 Rxf6 16. h3
$16) 14. Rad1 Rad8 {Both sides have finished their development and we do have
a nice center. However, it is under a lot of pressure and we will continue
next with a series of quiet improving moves. It's quite hard to come up with a
good plan for Black.} 15. Kh1 {A very typical positional move. We have a few
improving moves that we can play by hand- we do not need to think much. The
king gets away from this diagonal and also creates a square on g1 for the
bishop.} (15. Bf2 {We saw this in the same position with the queen on d7. Here,
Black has the amazing} g5 $3 {another point of the queen on e7.} 16. d5 Ne5 17.
Nd4 Nexc4 18. Qc1 {This position is still interesting but Black has got
counterplay.} Be5 $132) 15... h6 16. h3 {A useful move securing our kingside.
We are waiting for Black to show his hand.} (16. Qc1 {is another possibility.})
16... Rd7 {It looks like Black wants to double up on the 'd' file and put
pressure on our center. However, his main threat now is to take on d4 and
compared to the previous move the queen on e7 is protected.} (16... Bxd4 {
We should consider such moves all the time here but it does not work in this
position.} 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 c5 19. Rxf5 $1 {a key move} exf5 20. Qe3 $18)
(16... Kh8 {Black gets his king out of the way too.} 17. Bg1 $1 {Now we get
our queen to its favourite square on e3! It is a very nice multipurpose square.
} Rd7 (17... Nc8 18. Qe3 $16) 18. c5 $1 {It's time for us to take the
initiative.} Nd5 19. Bd3 $5 {We exchange one of Black's active pieces.} (19.
Bb5 $5 $146 {[%cal Gd2e2,Gf1e1,Ge1e7] This pin is annoying for Black.} Qd8 20.
Qe2 Rdf7 21. Ne4 $16) 19... Bxd3 20. Qxd3 Qd8 21. Rfe1 $16 {The queen can jump
to b5 and the knight will head to e4 soon. Black's king is weaker than ours.})
17. Bg1 {We allow Black to take on as the resulting positions are still in our
favour. If Black does not take the bait, we have a very comfortable middlegame.
} (17. Qc1 {We can avoid all tactical ideas but it is a slight concession.} Kh8
18. Bg1 $14) 17... Bxd4 $1 (17... Rfd8 18. c5 $1 Nd5 19. Bb5 $16 {Black is in
a lot of trouble here.}) (17... a6 18. Rfe1 $16 {[%cal Gd2e3,Ge3f4]}) 18. Bxd4
{The line is a bit forcing for the next few moves.} e5 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. c5 Nc6
$1 (20... Nbc4 21. Qe1 Nxb2 22. Bxe5 Nxd1 23. Bxd1 $16) 21. Qe3 {We force the
queens off the board. One of the general principles with the bishop pair is to
trade queens since they are even more powerful in endgames.} Qxe3 22. Bxe3 Rxd1
23. Rxd1 Nd7 24. Nd5 $14 {We have a very pleasant endgame with the bishop pair.
This is the best that Black can aim for.} *

