{[%evp 0,33,31,31,40,40,40,41,47,33,93,80,106,58,102,68,68,62,67,65,81,81,28,5,
-6,-30,9,5,77,89,93,72,47,22,101,81]} 1. e4 d5 {Another big favourite among
club players- the Scandinavian. People get very excited to bring the queen out
too early but it often backfires with the queen getting pushed around.} 2. exd5
Nf6 {This is a combination of the Alekhine and the Scandinavian. It is
slightly safer than the main lines but leads to more passive positions for
Black.} 3. d4 Nxd5 (3... Bg4 $6 {I have faced this in a few blitz games,
particularly at lower levels.} 4. f3 $1 {The most principled move forcing the
bishop back.} (4. Bb5+ {also gives a good edge for White.}) 4... Bf5 {By far
the most played move in the position.} (4... Bh5 5. c4 $16) (4... Bd7 5. c4 {
is just a clean extra pawn for us.} c6 6. Nc3 cxd5 7. cxd5 Na6 8. Bc4 Rc8 9.
Bb3 $16) 5. g4 $1 {This is the key idea to remember. A lot of the time we end
up not punishing such dubious lines by playing it safe. We need to go for the
critical lines.} Bg6 6. c4 e6 (6... c6 7. Nc3 {We do not rush with the move g5.
We can do it at our convenience.} cxd5 8. g5 Nfd7 9. cxd5 $16) 7. Nc3 $1 {
Black is unable to win the pawn back due to the threat of g5.} exd5 8. g5 Nfd7
(8... Nh5 9. f4 Nc6 10. cxd5 Nb4 11. f5 $1 {We are not afraid of the
complications. This is not forced though.} Bxf5 12. Qxh5 Nc2+ 13. Kf2 Nxa1 14.
Bb5+ Bd7 15. Bd3 $18 {White is just winning here. He will slowly be able to
win back the knight on a1.}) 9. Nxd5 Nc6 10. h4 $1 {No mercy for our opponent.
We need to play these lines energetically.} Nb6 11. Qe2+ Be7 12. h5 Bf5 13.
Nxe7 Nxd4 14. Nxf5+ $1 {We give up our queen for 3 pieces and attack against
the Black king.} Nxe2 15. Nxe2 g6 (15... O-O 16. Rh4 {A nice rook lift!} Re8
17. Kf2 c5 18. Neg3 {White was winning in 1-0 (49) Mukherjee, S (2253)
-Tedesco, M (2278) ICCF email 2018}) 16. Ng7+ Kf8 17. h6 $18 {White went on to
win easily in 1-0 (29) Tsikunov, A (2148) -Beer, D (2344) ICCF email 2018. We
can activate our rook via the 'h' file!}) 4. Nf3 {We do not rush with the move
c4. I have a general rule in openings to play the most necessary move first to
preserve flexibility. Here the knight belongs on f3 while we can play without
c4.} g6 {This is the most played move in the position but not the most
critical. We will build up a nice center and we have the potential to go for
play on the Kingside later.} (4... e6 {This is really sad and passive and
usually played by new players. It does not make sense to completely give up
the center and play slowly. I will just give a few moves to show our general
plan.} 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bd3 {The bishop can also just go to e2.} O-O 8.
O-O $16) (4... Bf5 $5 {This is not very common but objectively the best
according to computers. However, this in itself does not make it the best
practical choice- Black should not play the Scandinavian if he wants to play
the most objective moves :) It still leads to passive positions where we have
a clear edge.} 5. Bd3 $1 {We trade the bishops with tempo and get our queen to
d3. Exchanging one pair of minor pieces is okay and we still maintain a nice
space advantage.} Bxd3 (5... Bg6 {is way too slow.} 6. Bxg6 hxg6 7. c4 Nf6 8.
Qb3 Qc8 9. O-O $18) 6. Qxd3 e6 7. O-O c6 8. c4 Nf6 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Bf4 {I like
this square for the bishop in these structures. Next, we will bring our rooks
to the two central files.} O-O 11. Rad1 (11. Rfe1 Nbd7 12. h3 Re8) 11... Nbd7
12. Rfe1 Re8 13. h3 {I will give some sample lines in this structure and I
think it is very pleasant for us. We should preserve the minor pieces on the
board having space advantage.} Qa5 14. a3 Rad8 15. Qc2 h6 16. Re3 $14 {We can
play on either side of the board- go for c5,b4 or g4 at the right moment.}) (
4... Bg4 {This very rarely works in the Scandinavian but it is a common
response. We can often gain a lot of space with h3 and g4.} 5. c4 Nb6 (5...
Bxf3 6. Qxf3 Nb4 7. Qb3 $16) (5... Nf6 6. Be2 {We are not just going to castle
next. We want to go Qb3 and make use of our development.} e6 7. Qb3 $1 Nc6 {
is the move Black should make work but after} (7... Qc8 {is passive} 8. h3 Bh5
9. Nc3 Be7 10. g4 Bg6 11. Ne5 $18) (7... b6 8. Nc3 Nbd7 9. h3 Bh5 10. Be3 Be7
11. O-O-O $18) 8. Qxb7 Nb4 9. Qb5+ c6 (9... Qd7 10. Qxd7+ Nxd7 11. Na3 $16) 10.
Qa4 {Everything is defended and we just have an extra pawn.}) 6. c5 $1 {
I am repeating myself here- we have to exploit our lead in development and
center control with concrete play.} N6d7 {A sad square for the knight.} (6...
Nd5 7. Qb3 $16) 7. Be2 e6 (7... Nc6 8. Be3 $16) 8. h3 Bxf3 (8... Bh5 9. Nc3 Be7
10. Be3 O-O 11. g4 $1 {It is time to play on the kingside with a couple of
free tempi.} Bg6 12. Qb3 b6 13. h4 $18) 9. Bxf3 {We have the bishop pair and
much better-placed pieces.} c6 10. O-O Be7 11. b4 Nf6 12. Nc3 $16) 5. c4 Nb6 6.
Nc3 Bg7 (6... Bg4 {is as usual pretty bad} 7. c5 N6d7 8. Be2 $16) 7. h3 {
We stop Bg4 ideas. This seemed slightly strange to me as we usually go for
h4-h5. But it is more important here to maintain good control over our center
with Nc6 coming up.} (7. Be3 {allows an extra option in} c5 8. d5 Bg4 $5) 7...
O-O 8. Be3 {Black has to do something quick here to counter our center. This
is similar in all these g6 structures (the Grunfeld for example) . His only
trump is that our king is still stuck in the center.} Nc6 {The most popular
move preparing e5 but it is too slow and allows us to get our king to safety.}
(8... e5 {Black gives up a pawn but does not get enough in return.} 9. Nxe5 Be6
10. Be2 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. c5 $16 {We give up the d5 square but are a clean
pawn up.}) (8... c5 $5 {is maybe objectively the best but has been played very
rarely.} 9. d5 Na6 {Black is preparing the move e6.} (9... Re8 10. Be2 $1 (10.
Bxc5 {is too greedy} Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qc7 $44) 10... e6 11. d6 $16 {We keep the
'e' file closed. it is not easy for Black to win our d6 pawn.}) (9... e6 10.
Bxc5 Re8 11. d6 $16) 10. Qd2 $1 {We are prepared to reinforce our center with
Rd1 next.} e6 11. Rd1 exd5 12. cxd5 Nc7 13. Be2 {Black can win our pawn on d5
but at the cost of the important dark-squared bishop.} Bxc3 14. Qxc3 Nbxd5 15.
Qxc5 b6 16. Qd4 Qf6 17. Qxf6 Nxf6 18. O-O $14 {[%csl Ge2,Ge3] We have a clear
edge with the bishop pair.}) 9. Be2 e5 (9... Bf5 {Thank you very much!} 10. g4
$18) (9... Na5 {The knight ventures out to the edge of the board but does not
achieve much.} 10. b3 c5 11. Rc1 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Qxd8 Rxd8
15. O-O $16) (9... Re8 10. O-O e5 11. d5 Ne7 12. g4 $1 f5 13. Qb3 e4 14. Ng5 h6
{1-0 (24) Morozevich,A (2656) -Orlinkov,M (2293) Sochi 2018} 15. Ne6 $18) 10.
d5 Ne7 11. g4 $1 {Change of plans. After Black has partially closed the center
with e5 we are going to start an initiative on the kingside. Our king is
pretty safe on e1 and can castle any side, any time.} f5 12. Qb3 e4 13. Ng5 f4
(13... h6 14. O-O-O hxg5 15. c5 $18) 14. Bc5 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 f3 16. Bf1 Nexd5
17. h4 $1 $18 {All of Black's pieces are hanging and he is in huge trouble.} *

