{[%evp 0,31,31,31,41,47,49,71,106,89,99,60,89,75,59,69,73,70,64,59,54,53,47,46,
39,-7,78,14,79,81,58,58,62,56]} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 {This has
gotten popular over the last few years. The queen is safer here compared to a5
but also less threatening. He stops us from getting the bishop to the ideal
h2-b8 diagonal.} (3... Qd8 {I always felt strongly that this just could not be
sound wasting two moves with the queen and I had zero preparation against this
opening until I became a GM. In recent times it has been played by a few
strong players, albeit in mostly blitz games. There are a few ways to get an
edge here and we will try to go for the most ambitious one.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3
Bg4 (5... Bf5 {will as usual be met by} 6. Ne5 $16 {[%cal Gf1c4]}) (5... c6 {
This is a worse version of the Qa5 Scandinavian for Black.} 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5
e6 8. g4 $1 {The typical idea to deal with the bishop on f5.} Bg6 9. h4 $16) (
5... e6 {This is just sad for Black.} 6. Bd3 Be7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qe2 $1 {We want
to castle on the queenside and go for our opponent's king. It is the right
approach against such slow systems.} Nbd7 9. O-O-O c5 10. h4 $1 $16) (5... g6
6. Bf4 Bg7 7. Qd2 $1 {I just want to keep emphasising that we should go for
the initiative against such lines. Here we will castle queenside and try to
make use of the dark squared weaknesses on the kingside.} O-O (7... c6 8. Bh6
$1) 8. Bh6 {We do not even waste a second to castle queenside. Next, we can
take a call to either go for h4-h5 directly or castle first. I will give a few
sample lines here.} Nc6 (8... c5 9. d5 Qd6 10. O-O-O $16) (8... Qd6 9. h4 Bg4 (
9... Bf5 10. O-O-O {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. Ne5 $16) (8... c6 9. h4 $1
Bg4 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. Ne5 h5 12. f3 Be6 13. O-O-O $14 {[%cal Gd2g5,Gg2g4]}) 9.
O-O-O Nb4 (9... Bg4 10. d5 $16) 10. h4 Bg4 11. h5 $1 {Our only aim is to blast
open the kingside.} Bxh5 12. Bxg7 (12. Rh4 $5 $16) 12... Kxg7 13. d5 c6 14. g4
$1 Nxg4 15. Rxh5 gxh5 16. Qd4+ e5 17. Qxb4 $16) 6. h3 {We are happy to win
this important bishop and get our queen to f3.} Bxf3 (6... Bh5 {is rarely a
good idea} 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 $18) 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Be3 $1 {We want to castle
Queenside of course.} e6 9. Bd3 Nbd7 (9... Bb4 10. a3 Ba5 11. Qg3 {[%csl Re8]
Black is unable to castle.}) 10. O-O-O Bb4 11. Ne2 $16) (3... Qe5+ {I actually
faced this in an OTB game last year in Sitges and ended up not getting
anything out of the opening :) It is a favourite of Shimanov and there are
several games of his in the database.} 4. Be2 Bg4 {This is the point- he wants
to exchange the bishops and force our knight to e2.} 5. d4 Bxe2 6. Ngxe2 Qa5 7.
b4 $1 {I remembered this move being in my notes but did not understand the
point properly.} Qh5 (7... Qxb4 8. Qd3 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b7]}) 8. Qd3 $1 {
[%csl Rh5][%cal Ge2f4] We are preparing to go Nf4 next.} (8. d5 $6 {was too
hasty and Black managed to equalise easily.} Nf6 9. O-O e6 10. dxe6 Bxb4 11.
exf7+ Qxf7 $132 {1-0 (82) Arjun,K (2505) -Sattarov,B (2389) Sitges ESP 2022
The Week in Chess 1468 [arjun]}) 8... e6 9. Qg3 $1 {[%csl Gc7,Gg7] The queen
is well placed here keeping an eye on both g7 and c7.} Na6 10. a3 $16) 4. d4
Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {The most solid move stopping Nb5 ideas and preparing a square
on c7 for the queen.} (5... Bg4 {is not great directly.} 6. h3 Bh5 7. g4 Bg6 8.
Bg2 Nc6 9. O-O $1 $16 {This is the opposite of what we have been seeing so far.
Here we castle short anticipating Black to castle queenside.}) (5... Nc6 6. Nb5
$1 {Similar to the move g6 we are exploiting our lead in development and
playing for the initiative.} Qd8 (6... Qd7 7. d5 Nb4 8. c4 $16 {[%csl Rd7]
[%cal Gf3e5]}) 7. d5 $1 {We are going to chase the knight around.} Nb4 8. c4 e6
(8... Na6 9. Qa4 Bd7 10. Be2 $14) 9. a3 Na6 10. Qa4 c6 11. dxc6 bxc6 12. Nc3
Nc5 {The knight has been pushed around a lot and still has not found a stable
square.} 13. Qc2 e5 14. Be3 e4 15. Rd1 Qc7 16. Nd2 Bf5 17. Be2 $16 {[%csl Re4]
[%cal Gb2b4,Ge1g1]}) (5... g6 6. Nb5 $1 {These are the moves which we usually
forget, especially in shorter time controls. We want to exploit the queen on
d6 and the move g6.} Qd8 (6... Qb6 7. a4 c6 8. a5 Qd8 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Bc4 O-O
11. h3 $16 {The bishop on c8 is a big problem for Black in these positions and
we have also managed to gain space on the queenside for free.}) 7. Bf4 Nd5 (
7... Na6 {gives us a great position after} 8. c4 Bg7 9. Be2 $16 {1-0 (33)
Eljanov,P (2734) -Kasimdzhanov,R (2676) Douglas 2017 CBM 181 [Mekhitarian, K]})
8. Be5 $1 {This is the reason why we went for the move Nb5 after Black played
g6. We provoke some weaknesses on the kingside.} f6 9. Bg3 c6 10. Na3 Bh6 $1 {
Black is threatening to go Qa5 now.} (10... Bg7 {gives us a big edge} 11. Be2
$16) 11. Bd3 $5 $146 {We develop our bishop to its natural square without
worrying about opponent's threat.} (11. c3 {is perfectly possible.} O-O 12. Bd3
$14 {1-0 (55) Santos Latasa,J (2588) -Epishin,V (2564) Teplice 2019}) 11...
Qa5+ 12. Kf1 Na6 13. c3 Nf4 (13... O-O 14. Nc4 Qd8 15. h4 $16) 14. Bxf4 Bxf4
15. h3 $1 {We want to go g3 next and before that we need to cover the h3
square.} Nc7 16. g3 Bh6 17. Kg2 Be6 18. Qe2 $14) (5... a6 {This is a
non-developing move which does not fight for the center and breaks all known
principles. So it should be no surprise that Black's position is already
pretty bad even though many games have been played here.} 6. g3 $1 {g2 is the
best square for the light-squared bishop and we also prepare to go for the
move Bf4 next.} Bg4 (6... Nc6 7. Bf4 Qd8 8. Bg2 $16) (6... b5 {falls right
into our plans} 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O e6 (8... Nbd7 9. Bf4 Qb6 10. d5 $1 $18) 9.
Ne5 $1 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 Nbd7 11. Qf3 Rc8 12. Bf4 Qb6 13. Rfe1 $16 {White is close
to winning here with a huge lead in development.}) (6... Bf5 {was played by
Magnus in a blitz game but is too slow.} 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. O-O e6 9. Bf4 Qb4 10. d5
$18) 7. h3 $1 {We immediately force the bishop to choose its poison.} Bh5 (7...
Bxf3 {Thanks for the bishop pair but this may be the better move. It goes to
show how bad this line is for Black.} 8. Qxf3 Nc6 (8... c6 9. Be3 e6 10. O-O-O
$16) 9. Be3 e6 10. Bg2 O-O-O 11. O-O $1 $16 {Of course, we castle on the
opposite side and go for the king next.}) 8. Bg2 Nc6 9. d5 $1 {We need to
remember this idea- initiative! We have to exploit the bad placement of
Black's pieces.} Nb4 10. Bf4 Qc5 11. Be3 Qa5 (11... Qd6 {We managed to get the
move Be3 for free and that is too much for Balck to survive.} 12. Qe2 Nbxd5 13.
Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Rd1 $18) 12. O-O {This is already lost for Black.} Rd8 (12...
Nbxd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bd2 {[%csl Re8]} Qc5 15. c4 $18) (12... O-O-O 13. g4
Bg6 14. Nd4 $18) 13. Qe2 Nbxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bd2 $18) 6. g3 {Again we want
to fianchetto the bishop and prepare the move Bf4. I like this move also
because it is consistent with our general plans.} Bf5 {The bishop is safer
here compared to g4 and more active than on c8. But it does allow us to trade
the bishops on d3 with a tempo.} (6... Bg4 {The main move in the position but
in my opinion, not the best.} 7. Bg2 e6 8. O-O Be7 (8... Nbd7 {This takes away
the d8 square for the queen and makes it more vulnerable.} 9. Bf4 Qb4 10. a3
Qb6 11. b4 Be7 12. Na4 $16 {[%cal Gc2c4]}) (8... Qc7 9. h3 Bh5 (9... Bxf3 {
This may be objectively the best try but it is quite difficult to give up the
bishop pair for free in a practical game.} 10. Qxf3 Nbd7 11. Ne2 Be7 12. c4 O-O
13. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 10. g4 $1 Bg6 11. g5 Nd5 12. Ne2 {We are planning
to go c4 followed by Bf4 next. Very concrete play.} Nd7 13. c4 Ne7 14. Bf4 $16)
9. Bf4 Qd8 (9... Qb4 {Black cannot afford to go after the b2 pawn.} 10. h3 Bh5
(10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 $14 Qxb2 $4 12. Rfb1 $18) 11. a3 Qa5 12. g4 Bg6 13. Ne5
$16) 10. h3 Bh5 (10... Bxf3 {is pretty sad.} 11. Qxf3 O-O (11... Qxd4 12. Nb5
$1 $18) 12. Ne2 Nbd7 13. c4 Re8 14. Rfd1 $16) 11. Ne2 $1 {We are preparing the
move c4.} O-O 12. g4 {We take the chance to win the light-squared bishop and
also weaken Black's pawn structure.} (12. c4 Nbd7 13. a3 Re8 14. Re1 Ne4 15.
Rc1 Bg6 16. Nc3 Nxc3 17. Rxc3 $16 {1-0 (44) Vachier Lagrave,M (2760) -Tiviakov,
S (2570) Chartres 2022}) 12... Bg6 13. Ne5 Nbd7 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. c4 $16 {
1-0 (46) Dulany,L (2345) -Kreindl,H (2346) ICCF email 2014}) 7. Bf4 $1 {
I came across this idea while checking for the course and it seems to be a
very strong idea that fits perfectly with our overall plan. We are playing
concretely and energetically looking to castle queenside.} (7. Bg2 h6 $1 {
Black is trying to get the ideal setup with the bishop well placed along the
h7-b1 diagonal. It was recommended by Kotronias in his book- The Safest
Scandinavian and others. This has not been played much at all.} (7... e6 $6 {
is the main move but runs into} 8. Nh4 $1 {Black did not get his bishop to f5
to allow a trade on g6/f5. He has to stop this idea.} Bg4 9. Qd3 Be7 (9... Bh5
10. h3 h6 11. g4 g5 12. gxh5 gxh4 13. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1] We have a huge
lead in development.}) 10. h3 Bh5 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Bd2 $14 {
We will castle queenside and are ready to open up the kingside.}) 8. O-O e6 9.
Re1 Be7 10. Na4 $1 {We are preparing the move c4 to get control over the
center. This is the only way to fight for an edge.} (10. Ne5 O-O $11) 10... O-O
11. c4 Nbd7 12. a3 {[%cal Gc1f4]} Qc7 13. Qe2 $14 {The position is slightly
better for us but I would prefer the position in the main line.}) 7... Qd8 (
7... Qb4 8. Bd3 {We want to trade the bishops with tempo and quickly castle
queenside.} Bxd3 (8... Bg6 9. a3 $1 {The pawn is taboo} Qa5 10. Ne5 $16) 9.
Qxd3 Nbd7 10. O-O-O e6 11. Kb1 $16) 8. Bd3 $1 {Has been played only twice but
this is the point of our previous move.} Bxd3 (8... Bh3 $2 9. Ng5 $18) (8...
Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 $16) 9. Qxd3 {The queen is well placed here and we are
going to castle next. Where is Black's king going to go?} e6 10. O-O-O Be7 (
10... Nbd7 11. Kb1 Qa5 12. Ne5 $1 $16 {We are preparing to go Nc4 next. There
is no way he can castle Queenside.}) 11. Kb1 O-O (11... Nbd7 12. h4 $16 {
getting ready to open up the kingside.}) 12. g4 $1 {no time to waste!} b5 13.
h4 b4 14. g5 $1 {In opposite side castling positions the value of tempo is
very high and we do not waste any time.} Nd5 (14... Nh5 15. Ne2 $16) 15. Nxd5
Qxd5 16. h5 $16 *

