{[%evp 0,47,20,28,47,47,71,66,66,56,56,49,49,74,97,25,25,37,47,-4,11,-9,26,26,
19,16,15,19,19,30,21,0,0,0,31,-6,22,-30,-43,-46,27,14,21,23,23,24,2,-81,-79,
-79]} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 {The main line in the Scandinavian and
probably the most fighting line for Black. It is not completely sound but the
queen does have the potential to create some play on the queenside.} 4. d4 Nf6
(4... e5 {can simply be met with} 5. Nf3 $1 exd4 6. Nxd4 $16) (4... c6 {
Black anyway has to play Nf6 at some point so it does not have much
independent value.} 5. Bd2 $5 {We can however exploit this move order.} Nf6 6.
h3 $1 {We are ready to meet Bf5 with the move g4 and otherwise it is not clear
how Black can develop his pieces actively.} Bf5 7. g4 $1 Be6 8. Bg2 $16) 5. Nf3
{There are many different plans here for Black. Modern theory has established
that the best lines for Black are those with the move Bf5- either directly or
after c6. The other lines are more or less refuted with correct play.} Bf5 {
This is a safer square for the bishop compared to g4.} (5... Ne4 {Black is
breaking all the general principles jumping around with the knight.} 6. Bd3 $1
Nxc3 7. bxc3 Qxc3+ (7... g6 8. O-O $16) 8. Bd2 Qc6 9. Rb1 $18) (5... Nc6 6. Bd2
$1 {Black is unable to retreat safely with his queen.} a6 (6... Bg4 7. d5 Nxd5
8. Nb5 Qb6 9. c4 $18) 7. Bc4 {preparing the move Nd5.} Qh5 8. h3 $16) (5... c6
6. Bc4 Bg4 {As usual this is not a great idea for Black.} (6... Bf5 7. Ne5 {
transposes.}) 7. h3 Bh5 (7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 $16) 8. Bd2 e6 9. g4 Bg6 10. h4 $1 {
We create a big threat of h5.} Nxg4 11. h5 Bf5 12. Qe2 $1 $16 {[%cal Gf3h4] We
are preparing Nh4 and are going to castle long. It is very hard for Black to
get his king to safety without losing material back.}) (5... Bg4 {This used to
be the main line but he gives us too much space on the kingside and the bishop
keeps getting kicked around. Black is much worse here.} 6. h3 Bh5 (6... Bxf3 7.
Qxf3 c6 8. Bd2 Nbd7 9. O-O-O $16 {We castle queenside and can continue with g4
next with a much better position.}) 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 {in addition to his
problems with development Black's queen is in big danger. We always have the
idea to go Nc4.} e6 (8... c6 {allows} 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nc4 Qc7 11. h5 Be4 12.
Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qf3 Nd6 14. Bf4 $18) (8... Nbd7 9. Nc4 Qa6 10. Bf4 $1 {Preparing
the move Nd6. There is a huge difference in development between the two sides.}
Qe6+ 11. Ne5 Nd5 12. Bc4 N7b6 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Qf3 $18) 9. Nc4 Qa6 (9... Qb4
10. a3 Qe7 11. Bg2 c6 12. Bf4 $18) 10. h4 $1 {The bishop never gets a break.} (
10. Bf4 Qc6 {[%csl Rh1]}) 10... Bb4 (10... Qc6 11. Rh3 Bb4 12. h5 Be4 13. Nd2
$1 {g5 is coming up next with a crushing position for us.}) 11. h5 Be4 12. Rh3
$16 {Nd2 is a threat and it is very difficult to suggest something for Black.})
6. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge5c4] We are preparing both Bc4 and the even more deadly Nc4.
We need to play aggressively here to keep our advantage.} c6 7. Bc4 (7. g4 Be6
$1 $11) 7... e6 8. g4 $1 {A typical move in the Scandinavian. We play very
concretely making use of our development advantage.} Bg6 (8... Be4 9. O-O $1
Bd5 10. Bd3 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4] The bishop on d5 looks active but is vulnerable
in the middle of the board. We have a huge lead in development.} Nbd7 11. f4
Qb6 12. Be3 $16) 9. h4 Nbd7 (9... Be4 {does not make much sense directly} 10.
O-O Bd5 11. g5 $1 {A very powerful idea which wins for White.} Nfd7 12. Nxf7 $1
Kxf7 13. Bxd5 cxd5 14. Qf3+ Kg8 15. Qh3 $18 {[%cal Gf1e1] White is just
crashing through here.}) 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O {White's king looks
exposed but we can close the center after the trade on d5 and enjoy more space
and the bishop pair.} Bd5 {Black has to give up the bishop pair but he at
least ends up improving his pawn structure.} (12... Nf6 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bd3
$16) 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 Bd6 15. Bd2 Qb6 (15... Qc7 16. Qf3 O-O 17. Rfe1 $16
{We always have the idea of h6 in the air.}) (15... Qd8 16. Kg2 $1 $16 {
We need to meet the move Qh4 with Rh1. Otherwise, he can continue with Qf3 and
Rae1.}) 16. c3 O-O 17. Qf3 $1 {We do not mind giving up the pawn on b2. We
will have a lot of play along the 'b' file.} Bc7 $1 {Black prepares the move
Qd6.} (17... Qxb2 18. Rfd1 $1 Qb6 19. h6 g6 20. Rab1 Qc7 21. c4 $1 $16 {
[%cal Gc4c5] We will go c5 and Bf4 next.}) 18. Kg2 Qxb2 {Now. Black is up a
tempo compared to the previous line as Kg2 is not that useful.} (18... Qd6 19.
Qg3 Qb6 20. Bf4 Bxf4 21. Qxf4 $14 {We are threatening to go h6 next with a big
edge.}) 19. Rfd1 Qb6 20. h6 g6 21. Rab1 Qd6 22. Rxb7 Rfb8 23. Rxc7 $1 (23. Rb5
$14) 23... Qxc7 24. c4 $14 {We have tremendous compensation for the exchange
and if given the chance our bishops will dominate the board.} *

