{[%evp 0,17,20,8,44,8,82,77,71,70,96,70,75,35,41,42,75,15,54,46]} 1. e4 Nc6 {
This is often used when Black needs to play for a win at all costs.} (1... b6 {
I don't have a great opinion about 1...b6 and even 1.b3 :) Black allows us to
grab full control over the center and we should be able to get a sizeable edge.
} 2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3 {I like to keep the c3 square open for either the pawn or
the knight.} e6 (3... Nf6 4. Qe2 {Again we remain flexible regarding the c3
square.} Nc6 5. c3 {The pawn on c3 is perfectly restricting the knight.} e5 6.
Nf3 d6 7. O-O Be7 8. d5 Nb8 9. c4 $16 {We get a dream version of the KID.}) (
3... f5 $2 {I recently faced this in a bullet game and promptly went on tilt
after I failed to finish off the game (I knew it was losing) :)} 4. exf5 Bxg2
5. Qh5+ g6 6. fxg6 Bg7 7. gxh7+ Kf8 {This is where I messed up as my greed
took over.} 8. Nh3 $1 {Once the knight comes to g5/f4 the game is over.} Bxh1 (
8... Nf6 9. Qg6 Bxh1 10. Bh6 $18) 9. Ng5 $18) 4. Nf3 c5 (4... Nf6 5. Qe2 d5 (
5... c5 {is pretty bad due to} 6. d5 exd5 7. exd5+ Qe7 8. c4 $16) 6. e5 Ne4 {
The knight is not stable here and gives us the chance to open the center in
our favour.} (6... Nfd7 7. c3 c5 {transposes}) 7. O-O c5 8. c4 $16) 5. c3 {
is good enough maintaining control over the center.} (5. d5 $5 exd5 6. exd5
Bxd5 7. Nc3 {This is how we use our lead in development.} Be6 8. Bf4 $16 {
Nb5 is a huge threat and we have huge compensation for a measly pawn.}) 5...
Nf6 6. Qe2 d5 7. e5 Nfd7 8. O-O Nc6 9. h4 $1 $16 {An idea borrowed from the
French. We push our pawn to h5 and continue with Bf4 and Nd2. Black has no
counterplay on either side of the board.}) 2. Nf3 {Objectively, this is not
the most critical move because Black has the option to go for 2. ..e5 and
transpose. However, it should not bother you unless you intend to go for
something like the King's gambit :) Most players who go 1.. .Nc6 are intending
to get an unbalanced game and we will not give them that so easily.} d6 {
This is the only way I see Black fighting for a win and I have faced this a
few times against good players even in classical chess. It leads to slightly
unorthodox positions where the theory has not been established clearly.} (2...
f5 $6 {These funky ideas never work when we are going for objectively sound
moves with White.} 3. exf5 d5 4. Bb5 {We allow Black to win back the pawn on
f5 but get full control over the e5 square.} Bxf5 5. Ne5 Bd7 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. d4
Nf6 8. O-O $16 {The knight on e5 is a monster and it is going to be pretty
hard to activate the bishop on c6.}) (2... d5 {Now he tries to transpose to a
Scandinavian but the knight on c6 is not useful here.} 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qa5
(4... Qd8 5. Bb5 $16) (4... Qh5 {The extra option here but it fails to} 5. Nb5
$1 Kd8 6. d4 Bg4 7. Bf4 $18) (4... Qd6 5. d4 Bg4 {Black is going to castle
long and put pressure on our center. How to react?} (5... a6 6. d5 $1 {As
usual we play concretely to exploit our lead in development.} Ne5 7. Nxe5 Qxe5+
8. Be2 Nf6 9. O-O $16) 6. d5 $1 Ne5 7. Qd4 $1 {We immediately go for the
initiative.} Nxf3+ 8. gxf3 Bxf3 9. Nb5 Qd7 10. Qf4 $18) 5. Bb5 $1 {We exploit
Black's move order and force the bishop to a passive square.} Bd7 {The bishop
does not belong here but Black did not have much of a choice.} (5... Bg4 {
is too risky and we will destroy Black's pawn structure on the queenside.} 6.
h3 Bh5 (6... Bd7 7. O-O $16) 7. Qe2 O-O-O 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. g4 Bg6 10. Ne5 $18)
6. d4 a6 (6... O-O-O 7. O-O a6 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Ne5 $16) 7. Bc4 {Having forced
the bishop to d7 we can preserve the bishop on the board.} O-O-O 8. h3 Nf6 9.
O-O) 3. d4 Nf6 {Here there are a few options for us. I usually do not like
going for the move d5 early as it often leads to KID-like positions which is
what Black is aiming for. The move I always went for is 4.c3 which gives us a
pleasant edge. However, I feel we can play a bit more aggressively here and
make use of Black's risky play.} (3... Bg4 {This is the second most popular
move but it runs into the strong-} 4. d5 $1 Ne5 (4... Nb8 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3
$16 {We have the bishop pair and a very nice space advantage.}) 5. Nxe5 $1 {
We give up the queen for the initiative!} Bxd1 6. Bb5+ c6 {Black is not losing
the queen back but he will lose a lot of other material.} 7. dxc6 Qa5+ 8. Nc3
O-O-O (8... a6 9. b4 $1 $18 {we need to get the queen away from the 'a' file.})
9. Nc4 $1 Qb4 10. a3 Qc5 11. Be3 Qh5 12. cxb7+ Kxb7 13. Rxd1 $18 {A
fascinating position- we are completely winning even though we have only two
pieces for the queen. Look at the number of pieces on the queenside and the
completely exposed Black king.}) 4. Nc3 (4. d5 Nb8 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Gc7c6]})
(4. c3 $5 g6 5. Bd3 Bg7 6. O-O $14) 4... g6 {This is similar to the Pirc lines
which we looked at with the inclusion of Nf3 and Nc6. We can go for our usual
setup with Be3 and Qd2.} (4... Bg4 5. Be3 {We cover the d4 square and prepare
to go h3 soon.} e6 {Black wants to go for the move d5 and close the center in
his favour.} (5... e5 6. d5 Ne7 7. h3 $16) 6. d5 $5 {We act quickly gaining
space in the center.} exd5 7. exd5 Ne5 8. Be2 Bxf3 9. gxf3 $1 $16 {We will
castle queenside now and attack along the 'g' file}) (4... a6 {too slow} 5. d5
Nb8 6. Be3 $16 {We can go Qd2 and castle queenside next.}) (4... e5 {This is a
worse version of the Phillidor lines which we saw.} 5. Bb5 $1 {The knight on
c6 is not so well placed here.} exd4 (5... Bd7 {can be met with} 6. Bxc6 Bxc6
7. Qd3 $16) 6. Nxd4 Bd7 7. O-O Be7 8. Nxc6 $1 {We want to break his pawn
structure and the bishop is more valuable than our d4 knight.} Bxc6 (8... bxc6
9. Bd3 $16) 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. f4 $14 {We have a very pleasant edge with a
better pawn structure and control over the center.}) 5. Be3 Bg7 6. Qd2 O-O (
6... Ng4 7. Bg5 {We will preserve this important bishop for as long as
possible. The knight will be kicked back soon.} h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 e5 10. d5
Ne7 11. h4 $1 $16 {1-0 (41) Ter Sahakyan,S (2630) -Martinez Alcantara,J (2591)
Chess.com INT 2022}) 7. d5 {We first kick the knight back and gain some tempi.
It opens up the long diagonal but we will be trading the bishops soon.} Nb8 (
7... Ne5 8. Nxe5 dxe5 9. f3 $16 {Now the bishop on g7 is blocked and we can
castle queenside next with a huge edge.}) 8. Bh6 c6 9. O-O-O $14 {h4 is going
to follow next with a nice initiative on the kingside.} *

