{How to continue on the kingside?} 7. g5 $5 $146 {[%cal Gh4h5] We prepare the
move h5 and stop Black from going himself.} (7. h5 {was my first intention but
Black has the amazing move-} g5 $1 (7... gxh5 8. Rxh5 $14) 8. dxc5 Nxc5 9. Bxg5
{Now the position gets complex and Black gets some counterplay.} Qb6 10. Nd5
Qxb2 11. Rb1 Qxa2 12. f3 h6 13. Be3 Qa5+ 14. Qd2 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 $44 {We have
decent compensation here for the two pawns with the knight heading to b6 next.}
) 7... h6 {The only way to counter our plan.} 8. dxc5 {We need to release the
tension in the center first before going for our play on the Kingside.} (8.
gxh6 Nxh6 9. h5 Ng4 $1 $11) 8... dxc5 (8... Nxc5 9. Bxc5 {We are very happy to
trade the queens as the knight is stuck on g8.} dxc5 (9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 dxc5
11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {unfortunately fails to the amazing} 12. h5 $1 $16 {A very nice
tactical idea!} hxg5 13. hxg6 Rxh1 14. gxf7 $18) 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Rd1+ Kc7
12. Nd5+ Kc6 13. Bg2 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5] The knight is a monster on d5
especially if Black goes for the move e5.}) (8... hxg5 9. cxd6 Rxh4 10. Rxh4
gxh4 11. Nf3 $14) 9. gxh6 Bxc3+ $1 {Black gives up his dark-squared bishop to
damage our queenside pawn structure.} (9... Nxh6 10. h5 $14) 10. bxc3 Qa5 11.
Qd2 {This position looks great for us with the pawn on h6 but Black can get
enough counterplay after} Nxh6 $1 {This does not look too difficult to find
but the continuation is by no means easy.} 12. f3 Ne5 $1 (12... Ng8 13. c4
Qxd2+ 14. Bxd2 $14 {The bishop will be very well placed on c3 and we have the
bishop pair.}) 13. Bxh6 $5 {Looks winning for White but the computer manages
to hold miraculously which is practically impossible. There is very little
chance of all this occurring in our games.} (13. Kf2 Ng8 14. Bf4 $14 {White
has a slight edge here but Black could equalise with precise play.}) *

