{How to continue here?} 5. g4 $1 {This is the key idea to remember. A lot of
the time we end up not punishing such dubious lines by playing it safe. We
need to go for the critical lines.} Bg6 6. c4 e6 (6... c6 7. Nc3 {We do not
rush with the move g5. We can do it at our convenience.} cxd5 8. g5 Nfd7 9.
cxd5 $16) 7. Nc3 $1 {Black is unable to win the pawn back due to the threat of
g5.} exd5 8. g5 Nfd7 (8... Nh5 9. f4 Nc6 10. cxd5 Nb4 11. f5 $1 {We are not
afraid of the complications. This is not forced though.} Bxf5 12. Qxh5 Nc2+ 13.
Kf2 Nxa1 14. Bb5+ Bd7 15. Bd3 $18 {White is just winning here. He will slowly
be able to win back the knight on a1.}) 9. Nxd5 Nc6 10. h4 $1 {No mercy for
our opponent. We need to play these lines energetically.} Nb6 11. Qe2+ Be7 12.
h5 Bf5 13. Nxe7 Nxd4 14. Nxf5+ $1 {We give up our queen for 3 pieces and
attack against the Black king.} Nxe2 15. Nxe2 g6 (15... O-O 16. Rh4 {A nice
rook lift!} Re8 17. Kf2 c5 18. Neg3 {White was winning in 1-0 (49) Mukherjee,
S (2253) -Tedesco,M (2278) ICCF email 2018}) 16. Ng7+ Kf8 17. h6 $18 {White
went on to win easily in 1-0 (29) Tsikunov, A (2148) -Beer, D (2344) ICCF
email 2018. We can activate our rook via the 'h' file!} *

