{How to continue here?} 6. Nb5 $1 {These are the moves which we usually forget,
especially in shorter time controls. We want to exploit the queen on d6 and
the move g6.} Qd8 (6... Qb6 7. a4 c6 8. a5 Qd8 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Bc4 O-O 11. h3
$16 {The bishop on c8 is a big problem for Black in these positions and we
have also managed to gain space on the queenside for free.}) 7. Bf4 Nd5 (7...
Na6 {gives us a great position after} 8. c4 Bg7 9. Be2 $16 {1-0 (33) Eljanov,P
(2734) -Kasimdzhanov,R (2676) Douglas 2017 CBM 181 [Mekhitarian, K]}) 8. Be5 $1
{This is the reason why we went for the move Nb5 after Black played g6. We
provoke some weaknesses on the kingside.} f6 9. Bg3 c6 10. Na3 Bh6 $1 {Black
is threatening to go Qa5 now.} (10... Bg7 {gives us a big edge} 11. Be2 $16)
11. Bd3 $5 $146 {We develop our bishop to its natural square without worrying
about opponent's threat.} (11. c3 {is perfectly possible.} O-O 12. Bd3 $14 {
1-0 (55) Santos Latasa,J (2588) -Epishin,V (2564) Teplice 2019}) 11... Qa5+ 12.
Kf1 Na6 13. c3 Nf4 (13... O-O 14. Nc4 Qd8 15. h4 $16) 14. Bxf4 Bxf4 15. h3 $1 {
We want to go g3 next and before that we need to cover the h3 square.} Nc7 16.
g3 Bh6 17. Kg2 Be6 18. Qe2 $14 *

